# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: harold-garfinkel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall was born at Bermondsey in London, the second son of William Marshall (1812–1901), a clerk and cashier at the Bank of England, and Rebecca (1817–1878), daughter of butcher Thomas Oliver, from whom, on her mother's death, she inherited property.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall had two brothers and two sisters; a cousin was the economist Ralph Hawtrey.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] William Marshall was a devout strict Evangelical, "author of an Evangelical epic in a sort of Anglo-Saxon language of his own invention which found some favour in its appropriate circles" and of a tract titled *Men's Rights and Women's Duties*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Some scholars note this strict upbringing strongly influenced Marshall's work, citing the influence of philosophical idealism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall grew up in Clapham and was educated at the Merchant Taylors' School and St John's College, Cambridge, where he demonstrated an aptitude in mathematics, achieving the rank of Second Wrangler in the 1865 Cambridge Mathematical Triposlib.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall experienced a mental crisis that led him to abandon physics and switch to philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He began with metaphysics, specifically "the philosophical foundation of knowledge, especially in relation to theology".
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Metaphysics led Marshall to ethics, specifically a Sidgwickian version of utilitarianism; ethics, in turn, led him to economics, because economics played an essential role in providing the preconditions for the improvement of the working class.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He saw that the duty of economics was to improve material conditions, but such improvement would occur, Marshall believed, only in connection with social and political forces.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His interest in Georgism, liberalism, socialism, trade unions, women's education, poverty and economic progress reflect the influence of his early social philosophy on his later activities and writings.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall was elected in 1865 to a fellowship at St John's College at Cambridge, and became lecturer in the moral sciences in 1868.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He taught Mary Paley who became a lecturer at the then embryonic Newnham College, Cambridge; their marriage in 1877 obliged Marshall to resign his position as a Fellow of St John's College, Cambridge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] This coincided with his appointment as the first principal at University College, Bristol, which later became the University of Bristol, where he lectured on political economy and economics, alongside his wife, until he resigned in 1881.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He returned as Professor of Political Economy in 1882, leaving Bristol for good in 1883 when he was appointed a tutorial fellow at Balliol College, University of Oxford.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In 1885 he was appointed professor of political economy at Cambridge University, where he remained until his retirement in 1908.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Over the years he interacted with many British thinkers including Henry Sidgwick, W.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Clifford, Benjamin Jowett, William Stanley Jevons, Francis Ysidro Edgeworth, John Neville Keynes and John Maynard Keynes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall founded the Cambridge School which paid special attention to increasing returns, the theory of the firm, and welfare economics; after his retirement academic leadership of the Cambridge economists was taken up by Arthur Cecil Pigou and John Maynard Keynes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall desired to improve the mathematical rigour of economics and transform it into a more scientific profession.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In the 1870s he wrote a small number of tracts on international trade and the problems of protectionism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In 1879, many of these works were compiled into a work entitled *The Theory of Foreign Trade: The Pure Theory of Domestic Values*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In the same year (1879) he published *The Economics of Industry* with his wife Mary Paley Marshall.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Although Marshall took economics to a more mathematically rigorous level, he did not want mathematics to overshadow economics and thus make it irrelevant to the layman.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Accordingly, Marshall tailored the text of his books to laymen and put the mathematical content in the footnotes and appendices for the professionals.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Together, he and his wife completed *Economics of Industry* while at Bristol, and after publication it was adopted widely in England as an economic curriculum; its simple form stood upon sophisticated theoretical foundations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall achieved a measure of fame from this work, and upon the death of William Jevons in 1882, Marshall became the leading British economist of the scientific school of his time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall returned to Cambridge as Professor of Political Economy in 1884 on the death of Henry Fawcett.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] At Cambridge he endeavoured to create a new tripos for economics, a goal which he would achieve only in 1903.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Until that time, economics was taught under the Historical and Moral Sciences Triposes which failed to provide Marshall the kind of energetic and specialised students he desired.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Along with Pigou and Hawtrey, Marshall developed the quantity theory of money or the income version of the money theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In 1917, Marshall introduced the Cambridge version of the quantity theory of money and this was refined further by Pigou, Hawtrey, and Robertson.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] It became known as the Cambridge equation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall began his economic work, the *Principles of Economics*, in 1881, and spent much of the next decade at work on the treatise.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His plan for the work gradually extended to a two-volume compilation on the whole of economic thought.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The first volume was published in 1890 to worldwide acclaim, establishing him as one of the leading economists of his time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The second volume, which was to address foreign trade, money, trade fluctuations, taxation, and collectivism, was never published.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In a broader sense Marshall hoped to reconcile the classical and modern theories of value.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] John Stuart Mill had examined the relationship between the value of commodities and their production costs, on the theory that value depends on the effort expended in manufacture.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Jevons and the marginal utility theorists had elaborated a theory of value based on the idea of maximising utility, holding that value depends on demand.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall's work used both these approaches, but he focused more on costs.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He noted that, in the short run, supply cannot be changed and market value depends mainly on demand.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall pointed out that it is the prime or variable costs, which constantly recur, that influence the sale price most in this period.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In a still longer period, machines and buildings wear out and have to be replaced, so that the sale price of the product must be high enough to cover such replacement costs.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] This classification of costs into fixed and variable and the emphasis given to the element of time probably represent one of Marshall's chief contributions to economic theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He was committed to partial equilibrium models over general equilibrium on the grounds that the inherently dynamical nature of economics made the former more practically useful.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Much of the success of Marshall's teaching and *Principles* book derived from his effective use of diagrams, which were soon emulated by other teachers worldwide.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] This model is now used by economists in various forms using different variables to demonstrate several other economic principles.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall's model allowed a visual representation of complex economic fundamentals where before all the ideas and theories were only capable of being explained through words.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] These models are now critical throughout the study of economics because they allow a clear and concise representation of the fundamentals or theories being explained.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall is considered to be one of the most influential economists of his time, largely shaping mainstream economic thought for the next fifty years, and being one of the founders of the school of neoclassical economics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Although his economics was advertised as extensions and refinements of the work of Adam Smith, Thomas Robert Malthus and John Stuart Mill, he extended economics away from its classical focus on the market economy and instead popularised it as a study of human behaviour.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He downplayed the contributions of certain other economists to his work, such as Léon Walras, Vilfredo Pareto and Jules Dupuit, and only grudgingly acknowledged the influence of Stanley Jevons himself.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall was one of those who used utility analysis, but not as a theory of value.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He used it as a part of the theory to explain demand curves and the principle of substitution.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall's scissors analysis – which combined demand and supply, that is, utility and cost of production, as if in the two blades of a pair of scissors – effectively removed the theory of value from the center of analysis and replaced it with the theory of price.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] While the term "value" continued to be used, for most people it was a synonym for "price".
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Prices no longer were thought to gravitate toward some ultimate and absolute basis of price; prices were existential, between the relationship of demand and supply.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall's influence on codifying economic thought is difficult to deny.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He popularised the use of supply and demand functions as tools of price determination (previously discovered independently by Cournot); modern economists owe the linkage between price shifts and curve shifts to Marshall.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall was an important part of the "marginalist revolution"; the idea that consumers attempt to adjust consumption until marginal utility equals the price was another of his contributions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The price elasticity of demand was presented by Marshall as an extension of these ideas.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Economic welfare, divided into producer surplus and consumer surplus, was contributed by Marshall, and indeed, the two are sometimes described eponymously as 'Marshallian surplus.' He used this idea of surplus to rigorously analyse the effect of taxes and price shifts on market welfare.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall's brief references to the social and cultural relations in the "industrial districts" of England were used as a starting point for late twentieth-century work in economic geography and institutional economics on clustering and learning organisations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Gary Becker (1930–2014), the 1992 Nobel prize winner in economics, has mentioned that Milton Friedman and Alfred Marshall were the two greatest influences on his work.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Another contribution that Marshall made was differentiating concepts of internal and external economies of scale.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] That is that when costs of input factors of production go down, it is a positive externality for all the firms in the market place, outside the control of any of the firms.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] A concept based on a pattern of organisation that was common in late nineteenth-century Britain in which firms concentrating on the manufacture of certain products were geographically clustered.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Comments made by Marshall in Book 4, Chapter 10 of *Principles of Economics* have been used by economists and economic geographers to discuss this phenomenon.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The two dominant characteristics of a Marshallian industrial district are high degrees of vertical and horizontal specialisation and a very heavy reliance on market mechanism for exchange.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Firms tend to be small and to focus on a single function in the production chain.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Firms located in industrial districts are highly competitive in the neoclassical sense, and in many cases there is little product differentiation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The major advantages of Marshallian industrial districts arise from simple proximity of firms, which allows easier recruitment of skilled labour and rapid exchanges of commercial and technical information through informal channels.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] They illustrate competitive capitalism at its most efficient, with transaction costs reduced to a practical minimum, but they are feasible only when economies of scale are limited.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall served as president of the first day of the 1889 Co-operative Congress.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Over the next two decades he worked to complete the second volume of his *Principles,* but his unyielding attention to detail and ambition for completeness prevented him from mastering the work's breadth.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The work was never finished and many other, lesser works he had begun work on – a memorandum on trade policy for the Chancellor of the Exchequer in the 1890s, for instance – were left incomplete for the same reasons.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His health problems had gradually grown worse since the 1880s, and in 1908 he retired from the university.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He hoped to continue work on his *Principles* but his health continued to deteriorate and the project had continued to grow with each further investigation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The outbreak of the First World War in 1914 prompted him to revise his examinations of the international economy and in 1919 he published *Industry and Trade* at the age of 77.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] This work was a more empirical treatise than the largely theoretical *Principles*, and for that reason it failed to attract as much acclaim from theoretical economists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] In 1923, he published *Money, Credit, and Commerce,* a broad amalgam of previous economic ideas, published and unpublished, stretching back a half-century.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] He had shied away from controversy during his life in a way that previous leaders of the profession had not, although his even-handedness drew great respect and even reverence from fellow economists, and his home at Balliol Croft in Cambridge had no shortage of distinguished guests.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His students at Cambridge became leading figures in economics, including John Maynard Keynes and Arthur Cecil Pigou.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His most important legacy was creating a respected, academic, scientifically founded profession for economists in the future that set the tone of the field for the remainder of the 20th century.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Marshall died aged 81 at his home in Cambridge and is buried in the Ascension Parish Burial Ground.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Keynes wrote an obituary for his former tutor which Joseph Schumpeter called "the most brilliant life of a man of science I have ever read".
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] The library of the Department of Economics at Cambridge University (The Marshall Library of Economics), the Economics society at Cambridge (The Marshall Society) as well as the University of Bristol Economics department are named after him.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His archive is available for consultation by appointment at the Marshall Library of Economics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] His home, Balliol Croft, was renamed Marshall House in 1991 in his honour when it was bought by Lucy Cavendish College, Cambridge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] Alfred Marshall's wife was Mary Paley, an economist who was one of the first women students at Cambridge and a lecturer at Newnham College.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-marshall] She continued to live in Balliol Croft until her death in 1944; her ashes were scattered in the garden.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz was born on 13 April 1899 in Vienna, Austria, as the only child in an upper-middle-class Jewish family.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Following his graduation from high school, he was drafted into the Austrian Army where he quickly rose to the American equivalent rank of second lieutenant.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] His army regiment was dispatched to fight in a series of heavy battles on the Italian front (WWI).
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] In 1918, Schutz enrolled at the University of Vienna, where he earned his law degree.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He also enrolled at the Viennese Academy of International Trade from 1919 to 1920, specialising in international law.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] During his time at the University of Vienna, attending lectures given by Max Weber, Schutz came to the conclusion that Weber had left the problem of *meaning* unexplicated.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] As noted by Helmut Wagner (1983), Schutz's fascination with this problem was a result of his experience in combat, combined with returning to starving and economically decimated Vienna.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Partly because there were few academic posts available, he developed a well-established and prominent career in international banking, He became the chief financial officer for Reitler and Company, the Vienna banking firm.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] His academic work was done in his spare time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He was once described by Edmund Husserl as "a banker by day and a philosopher by night." In 1933, the threat of Adolf Hitler's rise in Germany caused Schutz and other Viennese intellectuals to flee Austria and seek asylum in allied countries.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz and his family relocated to Paris in 1938 in political exile.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He continued to work for Reitler and Company as an international lawyer.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He moved to the United States in 1939, where he became a part-time faculty member of The New School.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] There, he taught sociology and philosophy, as well as serving as chair of the Philosophy department.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz received a substantial amount of assistance from his wife, Ilse, who transcribed his working notes and letters from his taped dictations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz died on 20 May 1959 in New York City at the age of 60.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Four volumes of Collected Papers were published posthumously, along with the draft of a second book he had been working on prior to his death.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz was strongly influenced by Ludwig von Mises, Henri Bergson, William James, and Edmund Husserl, as well as Max Weber.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Drawing on phenomenology, Schutz's principal aim was to create a philosophical foundation for the social sciences.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] While Schutz's work paralleled George Herbert Mead’s analysis of the meanings within social interactions, Schutz was highly critical of Mead’s behavioristic approach.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Although Schutz was never a student of Husserl, he and colleague Felix Kaufmann intensively studied Husserl's work in order to seek a basis for Weber's interpretive sociology and for Austrian economic theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] In 1932, Schutz’s efforts resulted in his first published book, *Der sinnhafte Aufbau der sozialen Welt* ('The Meaningful Structure of the Social World') which was published in English as *The Phenomenology of the Social World*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz argues that social science must be grounded in analysis of what Husserl referred to as 'the natural attitude', the assumptions that structure everyday perceptions and actions in the social world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz retains Weber's conception of social science as properly committed to the principle of value neutrality, but also to value relevance, and that its investigations must rely on “ideal types”.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He viewed the technique of bracketing, drawn from Husserlian phenomenology, as a way beyond the limitations of ideal-type analysis.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] This publication brought him to the attention of Husserl, whom he visited frequently and corresponded with until Husserl's death in 1938.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Even so, when Husserl asked Schutz to be his assistant, he was unable to accept the offer at Freiburg University for personal reasons.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz's main area of concern was the ways in which people grasp the consciousness of others while living within their own streams of consciousness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He spoke much about intersubjectivity, in a broader sense, using it in reference to the social world, specifically the social nature of knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] A great deal of his work deals with the "lifeworld," in which people create social reality under the constraints of preexisting social and cultural factors and structures.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz is also known for his belief that humans attempt to typify everything; i.e., to categorize people and things to better understand them within the context of society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] He believed that the various typifications we use inform how we understand and interact with people and objects in the social world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz's theories and conceptions are illuminated through an intense and insightful correspondence with Harvard scholar Talcott Parsons.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] The thrust of the discussion centered on the meaning of the concept "social action." Whether the Schutz-Parsons correspondence can be characterized as “dialogue” rather than “debate” has been analyzed by Rehorick (1980).
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Further insights into the fundamental differences between Schutz and Parsons is provided by a critical examination of original correspondence that brought in a third scholarly voice—that of Eric Voegelin.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] This discussion shows that conceptual and theoretical differences between Schutz and Parsons stem from different “ways of knowing,” implying fundamentally different orientations toward social scientific thought.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz's writings have had a lasting impact on the social sciences, both on phenomenological approaches to sociology and in ethnomethodology (through the writings of Harold Garfinkel).
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Heavily influenced by Schutz's work as his student, Thomas Luckmann ultimately finished Schutz's work on the structures of the lifeworld by filling out his unfinished notes after Schutz died.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Berger and Luckmann went on to use Schutz's work to further understand human culture and reality, through the development of a new form of the sociology of knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Phenomenology is the study of things as they appear (i.e., *phenomena*).
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Phenomenology originated with Edmund Husserl, who Schutz studied and even met.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] There are many assumptions behind phenomenology that help explain its creation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] First, it rejects the concept of objective research: phenomenologists would rather group presumptions through a process called *phenomenological epoche*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Second, phenomenology believes that analyzing the daily human behavior will provide one with a comprehensive understanding of nature.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] The third assumption is that persons, not individuals, should be explored and questioned.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Sociologically speaking, this is in part because persons can be better understood by the unique ways they reflect and symbolize the society they live in.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Fourth, phenomenologists prefer to gather *capta*, or *conscious experience*, rather than traditional data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Finally, phenomenology is considered to be oriented on discovery, and therefore phenomenologists gather research using methods that are far less restricting than in other sciences.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Social phenomenology is concerned with how people use ordinary, everyday interactions to produce a feeling of reality and intersubjectivity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Most of Schutz's work concerned the methods used for the construction of reality through everyday experiences.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] The social construction of reality and ethnomethodology are disciplinary extensions beyond the social phenomenology of Alfred Schutz.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] As noted by Farganis (2011), phenomenological sociology is characterized as particularly subjective in nature because its emphasis of understanding reality through the perspective of the acting subject rather than through the lens of the scientific observer.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] There is this existence of meaning that comes into play, yet most people simply accept the world how it is and never second guess the concept or problem of meaning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz delves even more into specific relationships such as the difference between intimate face-to-face relationships and distant and impersonal relationships.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz's division of Husserl's *lebenswelt* (the mundane 'lifeworld') into four distinct sub-worlds is perhaps his most influential theoretical contribution.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] 2. social reality that is on the horizon of direct experience.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] The former consists of the *umwelt* ('environment'), the environment defined through the perception and action of agents.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] 3. the world of successors (*folgewelt*).
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] The last two represent the past and the future, whereas one's contemporaries share a community of time, if not space, and are different from the predecessors and successors because it is possible for them to become fellow-men or consociates.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] Schutz was interested in documenting the transition from direct to indirect experience and the series of experiences in between.
[src:harold-garfinkel/alfred-schütz] In his later writings, Schutz explored how everyday social experiences that pertain to these dimensions are most often intertwined in varying degrees of anonymity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The **American Sociological Association** (**ASA**) is a non-profit organization dedicated to advancing the discipline and profession of sociology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Founded in December 1905 as the **American Sociological Society** at Johns Hopkins University by a group of fifty people, the first president of the association was Lester Frank Ward.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Today, most of its members work in academia, while around 20 percent of them work in government, business, or non-profit organizations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA publishes ten academic journals and magazines, along with four section journals, including the *American Sociological Review* and *Contexts*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 2023 ASA had 9,893 members, making it a larger association of sociologists than the International Sociological Association.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In the United States, sociology was first taught as a college-level course at either Yale University in 1875 or at Indiana University in 1885.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The country's first sociology department was established at the University of Kansas in 1889, with the first sociology graduate program established at the University of Chicago in 1892.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The *American Journal of Sociology* became America's first explicitly sociological journal when it was founded at the University of Chicago in 1894.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] At first, American sociology was strongly influenced by European thought.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] German social science was particularly influential at this time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Early figures in American sociology, such as Albion Small, Edward A.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Ross, and Frank Wilson Blackmar became involved in an effort to distinguish American sociology from activities in Europe.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In the summer of 1905, George Washington University professor C.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Veditz began a discussion among sociologists throughout the United States, writing to several dozen people to gauge the need for or interest in forming a sociological organization.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Sociologists debated whether there was a need for a separate organization from the American Economic Association, American Political Science Association and the American Historical Association, which most sociologists at the time were members of.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Ultimately, a consensus was reached that the time had come for a society of sociologists in the U.S.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In early December, Veditz and eight others wrote to about 300 people inviting them to a special session during the American Economic Association (AEA) and American Political Science Association meetings later that month to discuss the potential formation of a sociological society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] On December 27, approximately 50 people, including one woman, gathered in McCoy Hall at Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, and, by its end, the group would motion to form a new society of sociologists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Though there would be debate as to integrating this new society with an existing organization, such as the AEA, the group would ultimately decide that the new society ought to be an independent entity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] At the end of the day of the initial meeting, those gathered at the meeting formed a five-person committee to develop a plan for the new society and how it should be governed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The committee members would re-convene the next afternoon to review the proposed structure of the society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Wilcox, Albion Small, Samuel Lindsay, D.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Lester Frank Ward was elected president, William Graham Sumner as first vice president, Franklin Giddings as second vice president, and C.W.A.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Charlotte Perkins Gilman was also a charter member of the society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] When the committee left Baltimore, the American Sociological Society was established.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] A constitution had been adopted, officers were elected, and plans were made for the second annual meeting of the new society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Vincent gave a presidential address titled "Countryside and Nation" which addressed economic and social conditions surrounding American agriculture.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Vincent's address has since been highlighted as a foundational moment for rural sociology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] According to Don Martindale, the Midwest exerted a strong influence over early American sociology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] By the middle of the 20th century, more than half of the presidents of the American Sociological Society were University of Chicago graduates.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The perceived domination of Chicago sociologists in the society and at the *American Journal of Sociology* prompted some society members to believe that they held "an undue influence in the affairs of the Society".
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 1935, this led to an annual meeting with "a distinctively anti-Chicago character".
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] A coordinated effort among those resistant to the Chicago influence, involving what Faris called "behind-the-scenes politicking", led to the election of a non-Chicago secretary and the establishment of the *American Sociological Review*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 1953, during the annual meeting in Berkeley, California, each of the (living) past presidents of the society composed a voice recording to address the coming generation of sociologists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 1981, in celebration of the association's 75th anniversary, Lawrence J.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Rhoades prepared a 90-page publication entitled *A History of the American Sociological Association, 1905–1980*, commonly referred to as the "1981 Rhoades History".
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The publication provides a brief overview of the founding and early years of the association, as well as highlights of key activities and events in the decades since.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 2005, in celebration of the association's 100th anniversary, ASA published a 201-page book entitled *A History of the American Sociological Association, 1981–2004*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The publication picks up where the 1981 Rhoades history concludes, continuing the story and capturing the association's history from 1981 through 2004.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] It was the culmination of over two years of detailed research by Katherine J.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA membership peaked at almost 15,000 in 2007 before declining to its current level below 10,000.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The trend led to the formation of a Task Force on Membership in 2016, with recommendations released in 2019, addressing issues of community, cost, and value.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In early 2010, ASA publicly expressed outrage over a controversy involving Frances Fox Piven and Glenn Beck, asking Fox News to stop Beck's comments.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] An article written by Piven concerning mobilization of unemployed individuals had spurred the commentary by Beck.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA suggests in their public statements that the line should be drawn at name calling and that political commentators should instead rely on gathering evidence related to the topics and then drawing the proper conclusions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Within the environmental sociology section of the ASA, in 2016 an ad hoc Committee on Racial Equity investigated racial and ethnic diversity within the section in response to critique that the section was overwhelmingly white.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Their assessment of the professional climate for scholars of colour concluded that the section was a 'white space' characterized by the overwhelming presence of whites and dominated by white leadership.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] They concluded that this situation acts as a barrier to inclusion of people of colour in the field, and that the field of environmental justice was likewise marginalised.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] From 2023 to 2024, in response to the war in Gaza, sociologists organized to request that the American Sociological Association establish a stance calling for a ceasefire and pursuing divestment from arms.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In December 2023, a letter signed by 125 sociologists including six former ASA presidents, asked for a statement in support of ceasefire.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The Sociologists for Palestine group responded to this by declaring that the council's removal of the divestment request from the resolution was "fundamentally undemocratic".
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In May 2024, 59% of voting ASA members approved the *Resolution for Justice in Palestine* and it was adopted.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In March 2026, Sociologists for Palestine submitted a petition for ASA members to vote on the boycott of Israeli academic institutions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] This would involve preventing Israeli academic institutions from advertising jobs and announcements via the ASA and subscribing to its journals.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] They boycott would also involve the ASA not advertising study-abroad or research opportunities in collaboration with Israeli institutions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The petition was signed by more than 400 people.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] On March 12 2026, a letter from ASA president Shelley J.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Correll and executive directory Heather M.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Washington said that the proposal was ineligible for members to vote on it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The letter said that this was because the proposal would have an impact on ASA governance matters and business operations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In the letter, Correll and Washington said that following the 2024 *Resolution for Justice in Palestine* "many members" had left the organization.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] However, critics of this statement noted that ASA membership had been largely unchanged, going from 9,923 in 2023 to 9,319 in 2024, then 9,433 in 2025.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] A petition in support of the letter from Correll and Washington gathered just over 115 signatures.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] From April 2026, Sociologists for Palestine organized a boycott of the ASA annual meeting.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] This involved ASA members not paying conference registration fees or booking accommodation with ASA hotels.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In addition, supporters of the group arranged parallel activities to be run elsewhere in New York or via online meetings during the conference period.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA moved the conference registration deadline from June 1 to June 15.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The Jewish Voice for Peace academic council issued a statement endorsing the boycott, describing ASA leadership's actions as an "anti-democratic refusal to put a member-led resolution to a membership vote".
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] By late June, Sociologists for Palestine said that over 800 people had signed up to this boycott.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The ASA also publishes *Footnotes*, a newsletter aimed at the association's members.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] *Footnotes* was established in 1979 and is published five times per year.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The ASA is governed by a code of ethics, which has been revised since 1970, with the first ASA code of ethics being written in 1970.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA members are bound by the code of ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The association also has codes for meeting behavior, disclosure, award revocation, and removal from leadership positions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In 1993, then-doctoral student Rik Scarce was jailed for more than five months as a result of following the ASA's code of ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Scarce's Ph.D. research was on the radical environmental movement.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Based on an FBI investigation of an Animal Liberation Front break-in, federal prosecutors argued in court that Scarce may have engaged in conversations with individuals believed to be involved with the incident.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Prosecutors demanded that Scarce testify to a federal grand jury about those conversations, but Scarce refused to answer three dozen questions, citing the ASA Code of Ethics and the First Amendment as his reasoning for remaining unresponsive.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Scarce's refusal to answer resulted in a contempt of court citation and 159 days spent in jail.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] He was never suspected of wrongdoing and—in keeping with contempt of court practice—he was never read his Miranda rights, arrested, or tried.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In January 2012, a United States district court ordered Boston College to turn over material from the "Belfast Project", an oral history project pertaining to the violence in Northern Ireland.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Boston College filed an appeal in February 2012, challenging the district court's decision.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA became involved in the case to help protect human participants from the subpoena of confidential project research data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The statement by the ASA council cited the potential damage this ruling would have on social science research by stifling the ability to study controversial topics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA is looking for an affirmation by the court for confidentiality in research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA style is a widely accepted format for writing university research papers that specifies the arrangement and punctuation of footnotes and bibliographies.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Standards for ASA style are specified in the *ASA Style Guide*, which is designed to aid authors in preparing manuscripts for ASA journals and publications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] In the fall of 2011, the ASA launched its "Sociology in Wikipedia" initiative.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Erik Olin Wright, President of the ASA, called for improvement in sociological entries in Wikipedia.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] He asked that professors and students get more involved by having Wikipedia-writing assignments in class.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The basic goal set forth by the initiative would be to make it easier for sociologists to contribute to Wikipedia, and for sociologists to become better involved in the writing and editing processes to ensure that social science articles are up-to-date, complete, accurate, and written appropriately.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The Portal would also provide instructions for professors on how to use Wikipedia writing assignments for academic courses.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The association's official archive was established in 1997 and is held at Pennsylvania State University's Paterno Library.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The archive does not contain material produced prior to 1931.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The archive includes material is split into eight series: Administrative File, Council, Committees and Sections, Funded Projects, Publications File, Organizations File, Miscellany, and Formerly Restricted Material.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The archive includes verbatim minutes of ASA council meetings and correspondence between ASA leadership.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The "American Sociological Association Annual Meeting" is an annual academic conference held by the association consisting of over 4,000 participants.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The meeting is held each August to provide opportunity for sociologists to share research, develop professional networks, give awards, and hold committee meetings.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The 2023 meeting had 4,802 attendees and featured 3,000 research papers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The first ASA meeting was held in Providence, Rhode Island in December 1906.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Meetings continued to be held at the end of December until the 1950 annual meeting in Denver, Colorado which was held in September.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Since then, annual meetings have continued to be held in August or September.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The 2020 and 2021 annual meetings were held online due to the disruption of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] The ASA presents awards to individuals and groups.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Additionally, the constituent sections of the ASA administer separate awards.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA has sections or sub-groups where sociologists with shared interests can interact.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] Each section has its own leadership team as voted for by section members.
[src:harold-garfinkel/american-sociological-association] ASA has additional communities for students, community college faculty, contingent faculty, high school faculty, sociologists in practice settings, and retired sociologists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophy is often contrasted with continental philosophy, a catch-all term for other methods prominent in continental Europe, most notably existentialism, phenomenology, and Hegelianism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The distinction has also been drawn between "analytic" being academic or technical philosophy and "continental" being literary philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The proliferation of analytic philosophy began around the turn of the twentieth century and has been dominant since the second half of the century.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Central figures in its history include Gottlob Frege, Bertrand Russell, G.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Other important figures include Franz Brentano, the logical positivists (especially Rudolf Carnap), and the ordinary language philosophers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine, Saul Kripke, David Lewis, and others, led a decline of logical positivism and a subsequent revival in metaphysics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophy has also developed several new branches of philosophy and logic, notably philosophy of language, mathematics, and science, and modern predicate and mathematical logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The **history of analytic philosophy** (taken in the narrower sense of "20th-/21st-century analytic philosophy") is usually thought to begin with the rejection of British idealism, a neo-Hegelian movement.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] But important precursors include the work of Gottlob Frege in formal logic and the philosophy of language, as well as the Austrian tradition associated with Bernard Bolzano, Franz Brentano, Alexius Meinong, and the early Edmund Husserl.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophy was significantly influenced by Austrian realism in the former state of Austria-Hungary, so much so that Michael Dummett has remarked it is better characterized as Anglo-Austrian rather than the usual Anglo-American.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In *Psychology from an Empirical Standpoint* (1874), University of Vienna philosopher and psychologist Franz Brentano gave to philosophy the problem of intentionality, or aboutness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] For Brentano, all mental events or acts of consciousness had a real, non-mental intentional object, which the thinking is directed at or "about".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Intentionality is "the mark of the mental." Intentionality is to be distinguished from intention or intension.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The School of Brentano included Edmund Husserl and Alexius Meinong.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Meinong founded the Graz School, and is known for his unique ontology of real, nonexistent objects; a solution to the problem of empty names.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This view is known as Meinongianism, or pejoratively as Meinong's jungle.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] According to Meinong, objects like flying pigs or golden mountains are real and have being, even though they do not exist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The Polish Lwów–Warsaw school, founded by Kazimierz Twardowski, was also influenced by Brentano.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Twardowski emphasized "small philosophy", or the detailed, systematic analysis of specific problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Twardowski was further influenced by the Bohemian logical realist Bernard Bolzano.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Gottlob Frege was a German geometry professor at the University of Jena, logician, and philosopher who is understood as the father of analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He advocated logicism, the project of reducing arithmetic to pure logic; supporting Leibniz and opposing Kant in the philosophy of mathematics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege developed modern, mathematical and predicate logic with quantifiers in his book *Begriffsschrift* (English: *Concept-script*, 1879).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege unified the two strains of ancient logic: Aristotelian and Stoic; allowing for a much greater range of sentences to be parsed into logical form.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] An example of this is the problem of multiple generality.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Neo-Kantianism dominated the late nineteenth century in German philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Husserl's book *Philosophie der Arithmetik* (1891) argued the concept of a cardinal number derived from mental acts of grouping objects and counting them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In contrast to this "psychologism", Frege, in *The Foundations of Arithmetic* (1884) and *The Basic Laws of Arithmetic* (German: *Grundgesetze der Arithmetik*, 1893–1903), argued that mathematics and logic have their own public objects, independent of one's private judgments or mental states.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Following Frege, the logicists tended to advocate a kind of mathematical Platonism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The modern study of set theory was initiated by the German mathematicians Richard Dedekind and Georg Cantor.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Italian mathematician Giuseppe Peano simplified Dedekind's work to systematize mathematics with Peano arithmetic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege extended this work in an attempt to reduce arithmetic to logic, developing naive set theory and a set-theoretic definition of natural numbers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege also proved influential in the philosophy of language.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Dummett traces the linguistic turn to Frege's *Foundations of Arithmetic* and his context principle.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege's paper "On Sense and Reference" (1892) is seminal, containing Frege's puzzles about identity and advancing a mediated reference theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege points out the reference of "the Morning Star" and "the Evening Star" is the same: both refer to the planet Venus.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Therefore, substituting one term for the other doesn't change the truth value (*salva veritate*).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] However, they differ in what Frege calls cognitive value or the mode of presentation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] One has to distinguish between two notions of meaning: the reference of a term and the sense of a term.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] As Frege points out, "the Morning Star is the Morning Star" is uninformative, but "the Morning Star is the Evening Star" is informative; thus, the two expressions must differ in a way other than reference.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] A related puzzle is also known as Frege's puzzle, concerning intensional contexts and propositional attitude reports.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Consider the statement "The ancients believed the morning star is the evening star." This statement might be false.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] However, the statement "The ancients believed the morning star is the morning star" is obviously true.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Here again, the morning star and the evening star have different meanings, despite having the same reference.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In Frege's paper "On Concept and Object" (1892) he distinguishes between a concept which is the reference of a predicate, and an object which is the reference of a proper name.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The paper "The Thought: A Logical Inquiry" (1918) reflects Frege's anti-idealism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He argues for a Platonist account of propositions or thoughts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege claims propositions are intangible, like ideas; yet publicly available, like an object.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In addition to the physical, public "first realm" of objects and the private, mental "second realm" of ideas, Frege posits a "third realm" of Platonic propositions, such as the Pythagorean theorem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] British philosophy in the nineteenth century saw a revival of logic started by Richard Whately, in reaction to the anti-logical tradition of British empiricism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The major figure of this period is mathematician George Boole.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Other figures include Scottish metaphysician William Hamilton, mathematician Augustus De Morgan, economist William Stanley Jevons, diagram namesake John Venn, *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* author Lewis Carroll, Scottish mathematician Hugh MacColl, and American pragmatist Charles Sanders Peirce.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] However, British philosophy in the late nineteenth century was dominated by British idealism, a neo-Hegelian movement, as taught by philosophers such as F.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Bradley's work *Appearance and Reality* (1893) exemplified the school.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophy in the narrower sense of twentieth-century anglophone philosophy is usually thought to begin with Cambridge philosophers Bertrand Russell and G.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell and Moore contributed to the philosophy of perception with a naïve realism and sense-data theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In America, the New Realists opposed idealism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] An important aspect of Hegelianism and British idealism was logical holism—the belief that aspects of the world can be known only by knowing the whole world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This is closely related to the doctrine of internal relations, the belief that relations between items are *internal relations*, or essential properties the items have by nature.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell and Moore in response promulgated logical atomism and the doctrine of *external relations*—the belief that the world consists of *independent* facts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In 1901, Russell famously discovered the paradox in Basic Law V (also known as unrestricted comprehension), which undermined Frege's set theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] However, Russell was still a logicist, and in *The Principles of Mathematics* (1903), he also argued for Meinongianism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] During his early career, Russell adopted Frege's predicate logic as his primary philosophical method, thinking it could expose the underlying structure of philosophical problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This was done most famously in his theory of definite descriptions in "On Denoting", published in *Mind* in 1905.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In this essay, Russell responds to both Meinong and Frege.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell uses his analysis of descriptions to solve ascriptions of nonexistence, such as with "the present King of France".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He argues all proper names (aside from demonstratives like *this* or *that*) are disguised definite descriptions; for example, "Walter Scott" can be replaced with "the author of *Waverley*".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This position came to be called descriptivism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell presents his own version of Frege's second puzzle.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The essay also illustrates the concept of scope ambiguity by showing how denying "The present King of France is bald" can mean either "There is no King of France" or "The present King of France is not bald".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell quips "Hegelians, who love a synthesis, will probably conclude that he wears a wig." For Russell, there was knowledge by description and, from sense-data theory, knowledge by acquaintance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell's book written with Alfred North Whitehead, *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913), was the seminal text of classical logic and of the logicist project, and encouraged many philosophers to renew their interest in symbolic logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] It used a notation from Peano, and a theory of types to avoid the pitfalls of Russell's paradox.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Whitehead developed process metaphysics in *Process and Reality* (1929).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell claimed the problems of philosophy can be solved by showing the simple constituents of complex notions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Logical form would be made clear by syntax.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] From about 1910 to 1930, analytic philosophers emphasized creating an ideal language for philosophical analysis, which would be free from the ambiguities of ordinary language that, in their opinion, often led philosophers astray.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Russell's student Ludwig Wittgenstein developed a comprehensive system of logical atomism, with a picture theory of meaning, in his *Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus* (German: *Logisch-Philosophische Abhandlung*, 1921), sometimes known as simply the *Tractatus*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The book starts, "The world is all that is the case." Wittgenstein claims the universe is the totality of actual states of affairs and that these states of affairs can be expressed and mirrored by the language of first-order predicate logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Thus, a *picture* of the universe can be constructed by expressing facts in the form of atomic propositions and linking them using logical operators.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The *Tractatus* introduced philosophers to the terms tautology, truth conditions, and to the truth table method.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Wittgenstein believed tautologies or logical truths *say* nothing, but *show* the logical structure of the world, and has been labeled a mystic who believed in the ineffable by some readers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The *Tractatus* further ultimately concludes that all of its propositions are meaningless, illustrated with a ladder one must toss away after climbing up it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] During the late 1920s to 1940s, two groups of philosophers known as the Vienna Circle and the Berlin Circle developed Russell and Wittgenstein's philosophy into a doctrine known as "logical positivism" (or "logical empiricism").
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The Vienna Circle (previously the Ernst Mach Society) was led by Moritz Schlick and included Rudolf Carnap and Otto Neurath.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The Berlin Circle was led by Hans Reichenbach and included Carl Hempel and mathematician David Hilbert.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Logical positivists used formal logical methods to develop an empiricist account of knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] They adopted the verification principle, according to which every meaningful statement is either analytic or synthetic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The truths of logic and mathematics were tautologies, and those of science were verifiable empirical claims.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] These two constituted the entire universe of meaningful judgments; anything else was nonsense.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Thus the principle rejected statements of metaphysics, theology, ethics, and aesthetics as *cognitively meaningless*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This led the logical positivists to reject many traditional problems of philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] They typically considered philosophy to have a minimal function, concerning the clarification of thoughts, rather than having a distinct subject matter of its own.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Schlick was a foundationalist, believing knowledge was like a pyramid, built on prior layers of knowledge except for the first layer.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Neurath was an anti-foundationalist, coherentist who famously gave the analogy of reconstructing a ship while on the open sea.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Friedrich Waismann introduced the concept of *open texture* to describe the universal possibility of vagueness in empirical statements.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Waismann never finished a book titled *Logik, Sprache, Philosophie* intended to present the ideas of logical positivism to a wider audience.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Carnap and Reichenbach started the journal *Erkenntnis*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Carnap advocated solving problems by "semantic ascent", talking about language instead of its objects.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Carnap also distinguished between trivial internal questions and meaningless external questions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He is best known for works like *Der logische Aufbau der Welt* (translated as *The Logical Structure of the World*, 1967) and *The Elimination of Metaphysics Through Logical Analysis of Language* (1959).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Several logical positivists were Jewish, such as Neurath, Waismann, Hans Hahn, and Reichenbach.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Others, like Carnap, were gentiles but socialists or pacifists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] With the coming to power of Adolf Hitler and Nazism in 1933, many members of the Vienna and Berlin Circles fled to Britain and the United States, which helped to reinforce the dominance of logical positivism and analytic philosophy in anglophone countries.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In 1936, Schlick was murdered in Vienna by his former student, Hans Nelböck.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Ayer's work *Language, Truth and Logic* introduced the English speaking world to logical positivism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] After World War II, analytic philosophy became interested in ordinary language philosophy, in contrast to ideal language philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Rather than rely on logical constructions, philosophers emphasized the use of natural language.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] There were two strains of ordinary language philosophy: the later Wittgenstein and Oxford philosophies.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Wittgenstein's later philosophy, from the posthumous *Philosophical Investigations* (1953), differed dramatically from his early work of the *Tractatus*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Philosophers refer to them like two different philosophers: "early Wittgenstein" and "later Wittgenstein".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The criticisms of Frank Ramsey on the "color-exclusion problem" led to some of Wittgenstein's first doubts with regard to his early philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Wittgenstein in the *Tractatus* thought the only necessity is logical necessity; yet that no point in space can have two different colors at the same time seems a necessary truth but not a logical one.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Wittgenstein responded to Ramsey in "Some Remarks on Logical Form" (1929), the only academic paper he ever published.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Ramsey died of jaundice the next year at the age of 26.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Prior to the publication of the *Philosophical Investigations*, philosophers like John Wisdom and Rush Rhees were some of the few sources of information about Wittgenstein's later philosophy; for example, Wisdom's work *Other Minds* (1952) on the problem of other minds.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The later Wittgenstein develops a therapeutic approach.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He introduces the concept of a "language-game" as a "form of life".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] By "language-game", he meant a language simpler than an entire language.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Wittgenstein argued that a word or sentence has meaning only as a result of the "rule" of the "game" being played.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Depending on the context, for example, the utterance "Water!" could be an order, the answer to a question, or some other form of communication.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Rather than his prior picture theory of meaning, the later Wittgenstein advocates a theory of meaning as use, according to which words are defined by how they are used within the language-game.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The notion of family resemblance thinks things thought to be connected by one essential, common feature may in fact be connected by a series of overlapping similarities, where no one feature is common to all of them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Games, which Wittgenstein used as an example to explain the notion, have become the classic example of a group that is related by family resemblance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He also famously uses the duck-rabbit, an ambiguous image, as a means of describing two different ways of seeing: "seeing that" versus "seeing as".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The other trend of ordinary language philosophy was known as "Oxford philosophy", in contrast to the earlier analytic Cambridge philosophers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Influenced by Moore's common sense and the later Wittgenstein's quietism, the Oxford philosophers claimed ordinary language already represented many subtle distinctions not recognized in traditional philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The most prominent Oxford philosophers were Gilbert Ryle, Peter Strawson, and John L.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Ryle, in *The Concept of Mind* (1949), criticized Cartesian dualism, arguing in favor of disposing of "Descartes' myth" of the ghost in the machine by recognizing "category errors".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Strawson first became well known with his article "On Referring" (1950), a criticism of Russell's theory of descriptions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] On Strawson's account, the use of a description presupposes the existence of the object fitting the description.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In his book *Individuals* (1959), Strawson examines our conceptions of basic particulars.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Austin, in the posthumously published *How to Do Things with Words* (1962), articulated the theory of speech acts and emphasized the ability of words to *do* things (e.g.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This influenced several fields to undertake what is called a performative turn.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In *Sense and Sensibilia* (1962), Austin criticized sense-data theories.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Samuel Alexander's realism influenced Australian philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The school known as Australian realism began when John Anderson accepted the Challis Chair of Philosophy at the University of Sydney in 1927.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] American philosopher David Lewis later became closely associated with Australia, whose philosophical community he visited almost annually for more than 30 years.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Findlay, a student of Austrian realist Ernst Mally, taught at the University of Otago.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Karl Popper lectured at the Canterbury University College in Christchurch.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In Sweden, Axel Hägerström broke away from Christopher Jacob Boström's idealism, founding the Uppsala School of Philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The Finnish philosopher Eino Kaila is considered to have founded Finnish analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kaila's student Georg Henrik von Wright succeeded Wittgenstein at Cambridge in 1948.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Chinese philosopher Zhang Shenfu first introduced Russell's ideas to China, and later translated the *Tractatus*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In 1920, Russell visited China at the invitation of Liang Qichao.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This begins the first phase of analytic philosophy in China.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Tscha Hung then introduced logical positivism to China with *The Philosophy of the Vienna Circle* (1945).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] During the second phase, scholars such as Jin Yuelin and Hong Qian spread analytic philosophy, until Communist political pressure sidelined research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] After the reform and opening up of the 1970s, analytic philosophy in China is now in its third phase, and is an active and growing area of study.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] During the second half of the twentieth century, analytic philosophy saw the demise of logical positivism and a revival of metaphysical theorizing.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kant scholar Wilfrid Sellars, the son of Roy Wood Sellars, "revolutionized both the content and the method of philosophy in the United States".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Sellars's criticism of the "Myth of the Given", in *Empiricism and the Philosophy of Mind* (1956), challenged logical positivism by arguing against sense-data theories and knowledge by acquaintance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In his "Philosophy and the Scientific Image of Man" (1962), Sellars's critical realism distinguishes between the "manifest image" and the "scientific image" of the world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Sellars's goal of a synoptic philosophy uniting the everyday and scientific views of reality is the basis of what is sometimes called the Pittsburgh School, whose members include Robert Brandom, John McDowell, and John Haugeland.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine shaped much of subsequent philosophy and is recognized as "one of the most influential philosophers of the twentieth century".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He is regularly cited as the greatest philosopher of the second half of the twentieth century, or the next great philosopher after Wittgenstein.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He was an empiricist who sought to naturalize philosophy and saw philosophy as continuous with science, distinguished only by philosophy being the most general science.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In his *magnum opus* *Word and Object* (1960), Quine introduces the idea of radical translation, an introduction to his theory of the indeterminacy of translation, and specifically to prove the inscrutability of reference.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The *gavagai* thought experiment tells about a linguist, who tries to find out what the expression *gavagai* means when uttered by a speaker of a yet-unknown native language upon seeing a rabbit.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] At first glance, it seems that *gavagai* simply translates with *rabbit*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine points out there is no way to tell that the speaker did not mean, for instance, "undetached rabbit-part" (such as its ear) as well as several other scenarios.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine's essay on ontology, "On What There Is" (1948) elucidates Russell's theory of descriptions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine uses Pegasus instead of "the present King of France" and dubs the problem of nonexistence Plato's beard.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The essay contains Quine's famous dictum of ontological commitment, "To be is to be the value of a variable".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] One is committed to the entities his theory posits by use of the existential quantifier, like "There are some so-and-sos".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Other parts of speech do not commit one to entities and so for Quine are syncategorematic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The paper made Quine the most dominant philosopher in America before Kripke.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Saul Kripke is widely regarded as having revived theories of essence and identity as respectable topics of philosophical discussion.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He was influential in arguing that flaws in common theories of descriptions and proper names are indicative of larger misunderstandings of the metaphysics of modality, or of necessity and possibility.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Modal logic was developed by pragmatist C.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Lewis to deal with the paradoxes of material implication.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Carnap also contributed to modal logic with works like *Meaning and Necessity* (1947).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Ruth Barcan Marcus introduced the now standard "box" operator for necessity and "diamond" operator for possibility in her treatment of the Barcan formula.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kripke provided a semantics for modal logic; he and Barcan both argued identity is a necessary relation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Especially important was Kripke's book *Naming and Necessity* (1980).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] For example, an election may have turned out differently, so the description "winner of the 1968 US presidential election" might have designated Hubert Humphrey instead of Richard Nixon.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] However, the name "Richard Nixon" designates the man Richard Nixon, regardless of the election results.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kant stated in the *Critique of Pure Reason* (1781) that necessity is the criterion for *a priori* knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kripke argued that necessity is a metaphysical notion distinct from the epistemic notion of *a priori*, and that there are necessary truths that are known *a posteriori*, such as that water is H2O, or gold is atomic number 79.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Kripke and Quine's colleague Hilary Putnam argued for realism about natural kinds.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Putnam's Twin Earth thought experiment is used to argue water is a natural kind.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] David Lewis defended a number of elaborate metaphysical theories.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In works such as *On the Plurality of Worlds* (1986) and *Counterfactuals* (1973), Lewis argued for modal realism and counterpart theory – the belief in real, concrete possible worlds, and argued against any "ersatz" conception of possibility.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] According to Lewis, "actual" is merely an indexical label we give a world when we are in it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Lewis applied Quine's dictum of ontological commitment to the statement "There are other ways things could have been;" committing Lewis (by his lights) to the real existence of other ways things could have been.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He also defended what he called Humean supervenience, and a counterfactual theory of causation, another view of Hume's.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frege questioned standard theories of truth, and sometimes advocated a deflationary, redundancy theory of truth, i. e. that the predicate "is true" does not express anything above and beyond the statement to which it is attributed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Frank Ramsey also advocated a redundancy theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Alfred Tarski put forward an influential semantic theory of truth, that truth is a property of sentences.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Tarski's semantic methods culminated in model theory, as opposed to proof theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In *Truth-Makers* (1984), Kevin Mulligan, Peter Simons, and Barry Smith introduced the truth-maker idea as a contribution to the correspondence theory of truth.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] A truth-maker is contrasted with a truth-bearer.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] A truth-bearer's truth is grounded by the truth-maker.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In response to the problem of universals, Australian David Armstrong defended a kind of moderate realism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] David Lewis and Anthony Quinton defended nominalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Polish philosopher Stanisław Leśniewski, along with Nelson Goodman, established mereology, the formal study of parts and wholes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Mereology was originally a variant of nominalism arguing one should dispense with set theory, but the now broader subject of parts and wholes arguably goes back to the time of the pre-Socratics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] David Lewis introduced the term 'atomless gunk' for something not made up of simples, which instead divides forever into smaller and smaller parts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Peter Van Inwagen believes in mereological nihilism, except for living beings, a view called organicism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] According to mereological nihilism, there are no (say) chairs, just fundamental particles arranged chair-wise.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Since John Locke's *An Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1690), philosophers have been concerned with the problem of personal identity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Locke thought psychological continuity or memory made one the same person over time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Bernard Williams in *The Self and the Future* (1970) takes the opposite view, and argues that personal identity is bodily identity rather than mental continuity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Derek Parfit in *Reasons and Persons* (1984) defends a kind of bundle theory of personal identity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Parfit issues the thought experiment of a case of fission, where one person splits into two, say surviving with half of their brain, while the other half is put into a new body.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] David Lewis defends perdurantism, where people are four-dimensional, so a person at any one time is only a part or slice of the whole person.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Peter van Inwagen's monograph *An Essay on Free Will* (1983) played an important role in rehabilitating libertarianism, with respect to free will, in mainstream analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] He introduces the consequence argument and the term incompatibilism about free will and determinism, to stand in contrast to compatibilism—the view that free will is compatible with determinism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Charlie Broad had previously made similar arguments.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Since Leibniz philosophers have discussed the principle of sufficient reason, or PSR.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Van Inwagen criticizes the PSR, while Alexander Pruss defends it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophy of time traces its roots to British idealist John McTaggart's article "The Unreality of Time" (1908).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] McTaggart distinguishes between the dynamic or tensed A-theory of time (past, present, future), in which time flows; and the static or tenseless B-theory of time (earlier than, simultaneous with, later than).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Arthur Prior, who invented tense logic, advocated the A-theory of time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Along with David Lewis's perdurantism, the theory of special relativity seems to advocate a B-theory of time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Eternalism holds that past, present, and future are equally real.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In contrast, presentism holds that only entities in the present exist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The moving spotlight theory is a kind of hybrid view where all moments exist, but only one moment is present.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Growing block, advocated by Charlie Broad, holds that only the past and present exist, but the future does not (yet) exist (there is also the reverse, a shrinking block).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Many-valued and non-classical logics have been popular since the Polish logician Jan Łukasiewicz.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Graham Priest is a dialetheist, denying the law of non-contradiction, seeing it as the most natural solution to problems such as the liar paradox.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] JC Beall, together with Greg Restall, is a pioneer of a widely discussed version of logical pluralism, the view that there is more than one correct logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Owing largely to Edmund Gettier's paper "Is Justified True Belief Knowledge?" (1963) and the so-called Gettier problem, epistemology has since enjoyed a resurgence as a topic of analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Using epistemic luck, Gettier provided counterexamples to the "justified true belief" (JTB) definition of knowledge, found as early as Plato's dialogue *Theaetetus*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Philosophers give alternatives to the JTB account or develop theories of justification to deal with Gettier's examples.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] For example, Timothy Williamson argues in *Knowledge and Its Limits* (2000) that knowledge is *sui generis* and indefinable.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] American philosopher Roderick Chisholm defended foundationalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Michael Huemer defends a type of foundationalism called phenomenal conservatism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Quine defended coherentism, a "web of belief", and thought all beliefs are open to revision; some are just held stronger than others, and so hold come what may.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Ernest Sosa proposed virtue epistemology in "The Raft and the Pyramid" (1980).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Alvin Goldman developed a causal theory of knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The debate between internalism and externalism still exists in analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Goldman is an externalist known for developing a popular form of externalism called reliabilism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Most externalists reject the KK thesis, which has been disputed since the introduction of epistemic logic by Jaakko Hintikka in 1962.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Fallibilists also often reject the KK thesis.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] How do we know? or What is the criterion for deciding whether we have knowledge in any particular case?
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Answering the former question first is called *particularism*, whereas answering the latter first is called *methodism*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] A third solution is *skepticism*, or doubting there is such a thing as knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Epistemic closure is the claim that knowledge is closed under entailment; in other words, epistemic closure is a property or the principle that if a subject S knows p , and S knows that p entails q , then S can thereby come to know q .
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Most epistemological theories involve a closure principle, as do many skeptical arguments (e. g. the dream argument).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In *Proof of An External World* (1939), G.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Moore uses closure in his famous anti-skeptical "here is one hand" argument.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Shortly before his death, Wittgenstein wrote the posthumously published *On Certainty* (1969) in response to Moore.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] While the closure principle is generally regarded as intuitive, philosophers, such as Fred Dretske with relevant alternatives theory and Robert Nozick's truth tracking theory of knowledge in *Philosophical Explanations* (1981), have argued against it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Others argue it is true but only given a specific context.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] In his book *Fact, Fiction, and Forecast* (1955), Nelson Goodman introduced the "new riddle of induction", so-called by analogy with Hume's classical problem of induction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Goodman's famous example was to introduce the predicates grue and bleen.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] "Grue" applies to all things before a certain arbitrary time *t*, just in case they are green, but also just in case they are blue after time *t*; and "bleen" applies to all things before time *t*, just in the case they are blue, but also just in case they are green after time *t*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Other, related topics of research include debates over cases of knowledge, the value of knowledge, the nature of evidence, the role of intuitions in justification, and abduction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Early analytic philosophers often thought ethics could not be made rigorous enough to merit any attention.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] It was only with the emergence of ordinary-language philosophers that ethics started to become acceptable.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Analytic philosophers have gradually come to distinguish three major types of moral philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] As well as Hume's famous is–ought problem, twentieth-century meta-ethics has two original strains.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Moore's *Principia Ethica* (1903), which advances non-naturalist moral realism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The work is known for the open question argument and identifying the naturalistic fallacy, major topics for analytic philosophers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] According to Moore, goodness is *sui generis*, a simple (undefinable), non-natural property.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Contemporary philosophers, such as Russ Shafer-Landau in *Moral Realism: A Defence* (2003), still defend ethical non-naturalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] After Moore's work, not much was done in analytic philosophy with ethics until the 1950s and 1960s, when there was a renewed interest in traditional moral philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Philippa Foot defended naturalist moral realism and contributed several essays attacking other theories.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Foot introduced the famous "trolley problem" into the ethical discourse.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] A student and friend of Wittgenstein, Elizabeth Anscombe, wrote a monograph *Intention* (1957) with an influential treatment of action.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Her article "Modern Moral Philosophy" (1958) called the is–ought problem into question.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Urmson's article "On Grading" also did so.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The second strain is founded on logical positivism and its attitude that unverifiable statements are meaningless.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] As a result, they avoided normative ethics and instead pursued meta-ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] The logical positivists thought statements about value—including all ethical and aesthetic judgments—are non-cognitive.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] As a result, they adopted an emotivist theory, also known as the hurrah/boo theory, valuing judgments expressed the attitude of the speaker.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] On this view, saying, "Murder is wrong", is equivalent to saying, "Boo to murder", or saying the word "murder" with a particular tone of disapproval.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Emotivism evolved into more sophisticated non-cognitivist theories, such as the expressivism of Charles Stevenson in *Ethics and Language* (1944)*,* and the universal prescriptivism of R.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Hare, which was based on Austin's philosophy of speech acts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Other anti-realist moral theorists include Australian John Mackie, who in *Ethics: Inventing Right And Wrong* (1977) defended error theory and the argument from queerness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Bernard Williams also influenced ethics by advocating a kind of moral relativism and rejecting all other theories.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] As the influence of logical positivism declined, analytic philosophers had a renewed interest in normative ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Contemporary normative ethics is dominated by three schools: consequentialism, deontology, and virtue ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] At first, consequentialism or utilitarianism was the only non-skeptical theory to remain popular among analytic philosophers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Henry Sidgwick's *The Methods of Ethics* (1874) exemplified the common theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Robert Nozick criticizes utilitarianism with the utility monster.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] John Rawls's *A Theory of Justice* (1971) restored interest in Kantian, deontological ethical philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Anscombe, Foot, and Alasdair Macintyre's *After Virtue* (1981) sparked a revival of Aristotle's virtue ethical approach.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] This increased interest in virtue ethics has been dubbed by some the "aretaic turn".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Similar to Aristotle's notion of *eudaimonia*, Władysław Tatarkiewicz proposed a conception of happiness as a full and lasting satisfaction with one's whole life.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Since around 1970, a significant feature of analytic philosophy has been the emergence of applied ethics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Difficult cases are often created by new technology or new scientific knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Topics of special interest include education, such as equal opportunity and punishment in schools, environmental ethics, animal rights, and the many challenges created by advancing medical science, such as abortion or euthanasia.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p01] Peter Singer argues for vegetarianism in the book *Animal Liberation* (1975).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] One of the most influential figures in the philosophy of law was ordinary language philosopher H.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Hart, who was instrumental in the development of legal positivism, popularized by his book *The Concept of Law* (1961).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Influenced by Hart and Ronald Dworkin, Matthew Kramer also proposed ethical (or normative) legal positivism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] During World War II, Karl Popper defended the open society in *The Open Society and its Enemies* (1945).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Isaiah Berlin had a lasting influence with his lecture "Two Concepts of Liberty" (1958).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Berlin defined 'negative liberty' as absence of coercion or interference in private actions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] 'Positive liberty' could be thought of as self-mastery, which asks not what we are free from, but what we are free to do.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Rawls introduced the thought experiment of the veil of ignorance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Rawls's colleague Robert Nozick's book *Anarchy, State, and Utopia* (1974) defends free-market libertarianism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] It is notable for the Wilt Chamberlain argument.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Another development was the school of analytical Marxism, which applies analytic techniques to the theories of Karl Marx and his successors.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Cohen, whose book *Karl Marx's Theory of History: A Defence* (1978) defends Marx's historical materialism, and is generally considered the genesis of the school.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Cohen jettisons the labor theory of value, and describes the structure of proletarian unfreedom, emphasizing power and freedom rather than labor-power and value.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Other prominent analytical Marxists include the economist John Roemer, the social scientist Jon Elster, and the sociologist Erik Olin Wright.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] These later philosophers furthered Cohen's work by bringing to bear modern social science methods, such as rational choice theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Although a continental philosopher, Frankfurt School theorist Jürgen Habermas is another influential—if controversial—author in contemporary analytic political philosophy, whose social theory is a blend of social science, Marxism, neo-Kantianism, and pragmatism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Communitarians such as Alasdair MacIntyre, Charles Taylor, Michael Walzer, and Michael Sandel use analytic techniques to challenge liberal assumptions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In particular, communitarians challenge whether the individual can be considered apart from the community in which he is brought up and lives.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] While in the analytic tradition, its major exponents often also engage at length with figures generally considered continental, notably Hegel and Friedrich Nietzsche.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Other critics of liberalism include the feminist critiques by Catharine MacKinnon and Andrea Dworkin, and the multiculturalist critiques by Amy Gutmann, Charles Taylor, and left-libertarians such as Hillel Steiner.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] While pragmatist George Santayana wrote *The Sense of Beauty* (1896), and British idealist R.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Collingwood developed a theory of aesthetic expressivism in *The Principles of Art* (1938), aesthetics was not addressed in the analytic style until the 1950s and 1960s, by the likes of Susanne Langer, Frank Sibley, Morris Weitz, and Nelson Goodman.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Since Goodman and *Languages of Art* (1968), aesthetics as a discipline for analytic philosophers has flourished.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Sibley, Weitz, and Goodman were anti-essentialists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In "The Role of Theory in Aesthetics" (1956), Weitz famously argues necessary and sufficient conditions will never exist for the concept 'art' because it is an "open concept".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Goodman thought art is not so different from science, and is another branch of epistemology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Arthur Danto argued for an "institutional definition of art" in the essay "The Artworld" (1964) in which Danto coined the term "artworld" (as opposed to the existing "art world", though they mean the same), by which he meant cultural context or "an atmosphere of art theory".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] There is also the historical definition, best exemplified by Jerrold Levinson.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Nicholas Wolterstorff emphasizes the social aspect of art, not as mere contemplation but as action.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Langer, Levinson and Wolterstorff have all contributed to the philosophy of music.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Guy Sircello's work resulted in new analytic theories of love, sublimity, and beauty.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] For Sircello, beauty is an objective, qualitative property.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] One author claims Sircello's theory is similar to Hume's.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Mary Mothersill sought to restore earlier conceptions of beauty in *Beauty Restored* (1984).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Roger Scruton also advanced theories of beauty.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] According to Kant scholar Paul Guyer, "After Wollheim, the most significant British aesthetician has been Roger Scruton." Scruton contributed to the philosophy of architecture.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Colin Radford and Michael Weston introduced the paradox of fiction in their paper "How Can We Be Moved by the Fate of Anna Karenina?" (1975) The paper discusses emotional responses to fiction, such as Leo Tolstoy's novel *Anna Karenina*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Their question is how people can be moved by things that do not exist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The paper concluded people's emotional responses to fiction are irrational.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] American philosopher Kendall Walton's paper "Fearing Fictions" (1978) addresses the paradox.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] This paper served as the impetus for make-believe theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Philosophy of language is still strongly influenced by earlier authors.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] According to one author, "In the philosophy of language, *Naming and Necessity* is among the most important works ever." Kripke challenged the descriptivist theory with a causal theory of reference.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Ruth Barcan Marcus also challenged descriptivism with a direct reference theory, in her case a tag theory of names.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Keith Donnellan too challenged descriptivism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Hilary Putnam used the Twin Earth and brain in a vat thought experiments to argue for semantic externalism, or the view that the meanings of words are not psychological.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Donald Davidson uses the thought experiment of Swampman to advocate for semantic externalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Tyler Burge uses the thought experiment of arthritis in one's thigh.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Kripke in *Wittgenstein on Rules and Private Language* (1982) provides a skeptical, rule-following paradox, undermining the possibility of our ever following rules, and so calls into question the idea of meaning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Kripke writes this paradox is "the most radical and original skeptical problem that philosophy has seen to date".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The portmanteau "Kripkenstein" has been coined as a term for a fictional person who holds the views expressed by Kripke's reading of Wittgenstein.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Alonzo Church pioneered intensional logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Czech philosopher Pavel Tichý developed transparent intensional logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Paul Grice and his maxims and theory of implicature established the discipline of pragmatics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Austin and John Searle also influenced the field.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Pragmatics focuses on deixis and presuppositions and other context-dependent features of language.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Analytic philosophy's interest in philosophy of language has arguably been superseded by an interest in the philosophy of mind.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Two common notions in analytic philosophy of mind are intentionality, as above, and qualia, a term introduced by C.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Emergent materialism holds that mental properties emerge as novel properties of complex material systems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] It can be divided into emergence which denies mental causation and emergence which allows for causal effect.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] A version of the latter type was advocated by John Searle, called biological naturalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The other main group of materialist views in the philosophy of mind can be labeled non-emergent (or non-emergentist) materialism, and includes philosophical behaviorism, type identity theory (reductive materialism), functionalism, and pure physicalism (eliminative materialism).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Motivated by the logical positivists, behaviorism was the most prominent theory of mind in analytic philosophy for the first half of the twentieth century.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Behaviorists believed either that statements about the mind were equivalent to *statements about* behavior and dispositions to behave in particular ways; or that mental states were directly equivalent to behavior and dispositions to behave.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Hilary Putnam criticized behaviorism by arguing that it confuses the symptoms of mental states with the mental states themselves, positing "super Spartans" who never display signs of pain.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Behaviorism later became much less popular in favor of either type identity theory or functionalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Type identity theory or type physicalism identified mental states with brain states.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Former students of Ryle at the University of Adelaide Jack Smart and Ullin Place argued for type physicalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Type identity was criticized by Putnam and others using multiple realizability.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Functionalism remains the dominant theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Computationalism is a kind of functionalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The view was first associated with Sellars.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Another functionalist was Jerry Fodor, who is known for proposing the modularity of mind, a theory of innateness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] He also introduced the language of thought hypothesis, which describes thought as possessing syntax or compositional structure (sometimes known as mentalese).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Searle's Chinese room argument criticized functionalism and holds that while a computer can understand syntax, it could never understand semantics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] A similar idea is Ned Block's China brain.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Dennett coined the term "intuition pump." Thomas Nagel's paper "What Is It Like to Be a Bat?" challenged the physicalist account of mind; so did Frank Jackson's knowledge argument, which argues for qualia.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Finally, analytic philosophy has featured a certain number of philosophers who were dualists, and recently forms of property dualism have had a resurgence; the most prominent representative is David Chalmers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Chalmers introduced the notion of the hard problem of consciousness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] He has criticized interactionism and shown sympathy with neutral monism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Kripke also makes a notable argument for dualism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Epiphenomenalism, the view that mental events are caused by physical events in the brain but do not cause anything else in return, is sometimes classed as a kind of property dualism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Yet another view is panpsychism, or the view that mentality is fundamental and ubiquitous in the natural world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Panpsychism can be contrasted with idealism by still believing in matter.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In recent years, a central focus of research in the philosophy of mind has been consciousness and the philosophy of perception.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The homunculus argument is an objection raised against many older theories of perception.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] While there is now a general consensus for the global neuronal workspace model of consciousness, there are many opinions as to the specifics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The best known theories in analytic philosophy are Searle's naive realism, Fred Dretske and Michael Tye's representationalism, Dennett's heterophenomenology, and the higher-order theories of either David M.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Rosenthal—who advocates a higher-order thought (HOT) model—or David Armstrong and William Lycan—who advocate a higher-order perception (HOP) model.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Kurt Gödel, a student of Hans Hahn of the Vienna Circle, produced his incompleteness theorems showing that *Principia Mathematica* also failed to reduce arithmetic to logic, and that Hilbert's program was unattainable.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Ernst Zermelo and Abraham Fraenkel established Zermelo Fraenkel Set Theory (with the axiom of choice, abbreviated as ZFC).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Quine developed his own system, dubbed New Foundations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Physicist Eugene Wigner's seminal paper "The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Mathematics in the Natural Sciences" (1960) poses the question of why a formal pursuit like mathematics can have real utility.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Hilbert's Hotel shows some of the counterintuitive properties of infinite sets.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] José Benardete in *Infinity: An Essay in Metaphysics* (1964) argued for the reality of infinity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The Grim Reaper paradox stems from his work.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Akin to the medieval debate on universals, between realists, idealists, and nominalists; the philosophy of mathematics has the debate between logicists or platonists, conceptualists or intuitionists, and formalists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Gödel was a platonist who postulated a special kind of intuition that lets one perceive mathematical objects directly.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Quine and Putnam argued for platonism with the indispensability argument.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Edward Zalta devised abstract object theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Crispin Wright, along with Bob Hale, led a Neo-Fregean revival with the work *Frege's Conception of Numbers as Objects* (1983).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Physicist Roger Penrose is also a mathematical platonist, in works like *The Road to Reality* (2004).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Structuralist Paul Benacerraf has two well-known objections to mathematical platonism; one is about identification, and the other epistemological.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In the latter, Benacerraf argues that while platonism explains mathematical semantics, it does not simultaneously explain mathematical knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] It is hard to know anything about a far-removed, platonic object.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Predicativism is another alternative to platonism, utilizing Henri Poincaré's response to Russell's paradox.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] There are also Aristotelians in mathematics, such as Dale Jacquette.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The intuitionists, led by Dutch mathematician L.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Brouwer, are a constructivist school which sees mathematics as a cognitive construct rather than a type of objective truth.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Brouwer also influenced Wittgenstein's abandonment of the *Tractatus*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The formalists, best exemplified by David Hilbert, considered mathematics to be merely the investigation of formal axiom systems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Hartry Field defended mathematical fictionalism in *Science Without Numbers* (1980), arguing numbers are dispensable.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Analytic philosophy tended to avoid the study of religion, largely dismissing (as per the logical positivists) the subject as a part of metaphysics and therefore meaningless.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The Society of Christian Philosophers was established in 1978.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Analytic philosophy formed the basis for some sophisticated Christian arguments, such as those of the reformed epistemologists including Alvin Plantinga, William Alston, and Nicholas Wolterstorff.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Plantinga was once described by *Time* magazine as "America's leading orthodox Protestant philosopher of God".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] His seminal work *God and Other Minds* (1967) argues belief in God is a properly basic belief akin to the belief in other minds.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Plantinga also developed a modal ontological argument in *The Nature of Necessity* (1974).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Plantinga, John Mackie, and Antony Flew debated the use of the *free will defense* as a way to solve the problem of evil.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Plantinga further issued a trilogy on epistemology, *Warrant: The Current Debate* (1993), *Warrant and Proper Function* (1993), and *Warranted Christian Belief* (2000).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Plantinga's evolutionary argument against naturalism contends there is a problem in asserting both evolution and naturalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Robert Merrihew Adams also defended divine command theory, and the virtue of faith.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] William Lane Craig defends the Kalam cosmological argument in the book of the same name.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Catholic analytic philosophers—such as Elizabeth Anscombe, her husband Peter Geach, MacIntyre, Anthony Kenny, John Haldane, Eleonore Stump, and others—developed Analytic Thomism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Orthodox convert Richard Swinburne wrote a trilogy of books arguing for God, *The Coherence of Theism* (1977), *The Existence of God* (1979), and *Faith and Reason* (1981).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Swinburne is notable for his belief that God's existence is contingent rather than necessary (it is possible God does not exist), but that nonetheless He does exist as a brute fact.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The analytic philosophy of religion has been preoccupied with Wittgenstein, as well as his interpretation of Søren Kierkegaard.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Wittgenstein fought for the Austrian army in World War I and came upon a copy of Leo Tolstoy's *The Gospel in Brief* (1896).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] He subsequently underwent some kind of religious conversion.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] "Swansea school" philosophers such as Rush Rhees, Peter Winch, and D.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Phillips, among others, founded a school of religious thought based on Wittgenstein.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The name "contemplative philosophy" was coined by Phillips in *Philosophy's Cool Place* (1999), after a passage quoted in Wittgenstein's *Culture and Value* (1980).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The weight given to scientific evidence is largely due to philosophers' commitments to scientific realism and naturalism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Some such as Friedrich Hayek in *The Counter-Revolution of Science* (1952) see using science in philosophy as scientism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Nonetheless, science has had an increasingly significant role in analytic philosophy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The theory of special relativity has had a profound effect on the philosophy of time, and quantum physics is routinely discussed in the free will debate.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Ernest Nagel's book *The Structure of Science* (1961) practically inaugurated the field of philosophy of science.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Carl Hempel advocated confirmation theory or Bayesian epistemology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] He introduced the famous raven's paradox.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In reaction to what he considered excesses of logical positivism, Karl Popper, in *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* (1959), rejects the standard inductivist views on the scientific method in favor of a highly influential theory of falsification, using it to solve the demarcation problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Quine and French scientist Pierre Duhem seemed to have similar views in certain respects.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The Duhem–Quine thesis, or problem of underdetermination, posits that no scientific hypothesis can be understood in isolation, a viewpoint called confirmation holism.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Following Quine and Duhem, subsequent theories emphasized theory-ladenness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] In reaction to both the logical positivists and Popper, philosophy became dominated by social constructivist and cognitive relativist theories of science.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Significant for these discussions is Thomas Kuhn, who in *The Structure of Scientific Revolutions* (1962) formulated the idea of paradigm shifts and sparked a "revolt against positivism" known as the "historical turn".
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Paul Feyerabend's book *Against Method* (1975) advocates epistemological anarchism; that there are no universal rules for scientific inquiry.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Philosophers like Tim Maudlin focus on the philosophy of physics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Maudlin argues in *The Metaphysics Within Physics* (2007) that philosophy must reflect on physics, and that scientific laws are *sui generis*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Recently there has also been work in the philosophy of chemistry, and the philosophy of biology has undergone considerable growth, especially due to the debate over the nature of evolution, particularly natural selection.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Daniel Dennett and his book *Darwin's Dangerous Idea* (1995), which defends Neo-Darwinism, stand at the forefront of this debate.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Jerry Fodor criticizes natural selection in *What Darwin Got Wrong* (2010).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] The philosophy of social science has also received increased interest.
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Peter Winch takes a Wittgensteinian perspective in *The Idea of a Social Science and its Relation to Philosophy* (1958).
[src:harold-garfinkel/analytic-philosophy-p02] Searle contributed to social ontology and the theory of social constructs with *The Construction of Social Reality* (1995).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] High-profile applications of AI include advanced web search engines, chatbots, virtual assistants, autonomous vehicles, and play and analysis in strategy games (e.g., chess and Go).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Since the 2020s, generative AI has become widely available to generate images, audio, and videos from text prompts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traditional goals of AI research include learning, reasoning, knowledge representation, planning, natural language processing, and perception, as well as support for robotics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] To reach these goals, AI researchers have used techniques including state space search and mathematical optimization, formal logic, artificial neural networks, and methods based on statistics, operations research, and economics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI also draws upon psychology, linguistics, philosophy, neuroscience, and other fields.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Some companies, such as OpenAI, Google DeepMind and Meta, aim to create artificial general intelligence (AGI) – AI that can complete virtually any cognitive task at least as well as a human.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Artificial intelligence was founded as an academic discipline in 1956, and the field went through multiple cycles of optimism throughout its history, followed by periods of disappointment and loss of funding, known as AI winters.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Funding and interest increased substantially after 2012, when graphics processing units began being used to accelerate neural networks, and deep learning outperformed previous AI techniques.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] This growth accelerated further after 2017 with the transformer architecture.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the 2020s, an AI boom has coincided with advances in generative AI, which allowed for the creation and modification of media.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In addition to AI safety and unintended consequences and harms from the use of AI, ethical concerns, AI's long-term effects, and potential existential risks have prompted discussions of AI regulation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The general problem of simulating (or creating) intelligence has been broken into subproblems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These consist of particular traits or capabilities that researchers expect an intelligent system to display.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traits described below have received the most attention and cover the scope of AI research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early researchers developed algorithms that imitated step-by-step reasoning that humans use when they solve puzzles or make logical deductions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] By the late 1980s and 1990s, methods were developed for dealing with uncertain or incomplete information, employing concepts from probability and economics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many of these algorithms are insufficient for solving large reasoning problems because they experience a "combinatorial explosion": They become exponentially slower as the problems grow.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Even humans rarely use the step-by-step deduction that early AI research could model.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Humans solve most of their problems using fast, intuitive judgments.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Reasoning models, a type of large language model trained to generate intermediate chains-of-thought, emerged in 2024 and allowed improved performance on complex problems in mathematics and coding.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Knowledge representation and knowledge engineering allow AI programs to answer questions intelligently and make deductions about real-world facts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal knowledge representations are used in content-based indexing and retrieval, scene interpretation, clinical decision support, knowledge discovery (mining "interesting" and actionable inferences from large databases), and other areas.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A knowledge base is a body of knowledge represented in a form that can be used by a program.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] An ontology is the set of objects, relations, concepts, and properties used by a particular domain of knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is also the difficulty of knowledge acquisition, the problem of obtaining knowledge for AI applications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] An "agent" is any entity (artificial or not) that perceives and takes actions in the world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A rational agent has goals or preferences and takes actions to make them happen.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated planning, the agent has a specific goal.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated decision-making, the agent has preferences—there are some situations it would prefer to be in, and some situations it is trying to avoid.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision-making agent assigns a number to each situation (called its "utility") that measures how much the agent prefers it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] For each possible action, it can calculate the "expected utility": the utility of all possible outcomes of the action, weighted by the probability that the outcome will occur.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can then choose the action with the maximum expected utility.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In classical planning, the agent knows exactly what the effect of any action will be.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In most real-world problems, however, the agent may not be certain about the situation it is in (it is "unknown" or "unobservable") and it may not know for certain what will happen after each possible action (it is not "deterministic").
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It must choose an action by making a probabilistic guess and then reassess the situation to see if the action worked.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Alongside thorough testing and improvement based on previous decisions, having an explanation for why the agent took certain decisions is a way to build trust, especially when the decisions have to be relied upon.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In some problems, the agent's preferences may be uncertain, especially if there are other agents or humans involved.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These preferences be learned (e.g., with inverse reinforcement learning), or the agent can seek information to improve them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Information value theory can be used to weigh the value of exploratory or experimental actions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The space of possible future actions and situations is typically intractably large, so the agents must take actions and evaluate situations while being uncertain of what the outcome will be.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A Markov decision process has a transition model that describes the probability that a particular action will change the state in a particular way and a reward function that supplies the utility of each state and the cost of each action.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A policy associates a decision with each possible state.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The policy could be calculated (e.g., by iteration), be heuristic, or it can be learned.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game theory describes the rational behavior of multiple interacting agents and is used in AI programs that make decisions that involve other agents.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine learning is the study of programs that can improve their performance on a given task automatically.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It has been a part of AI from the beginning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are several kinds of machine learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Unsupervised learning analyzes a stream of data and finds patterns and makes predictions without any other guidance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Supervised learning requires labeling the training data with the expected answers, and comes in two main varieties: classification (where the program must learn to predict what category the input belongs in) and regression (where the program must deduce a numeric function based on numeric input).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In reinforcement learning, the agent is rewarded for good responses and punished for bad ones.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The agent learns to choose responses that are classified as "good".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Transfer learning is when the knowledge gained from one problem is applied to a new problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning is a type of machine learning that runs inputs through biologically inspired artificial neural networks for all of these types of learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computational learning theory can assess learners by computational complexity, by sample complexity (how much data is required), or by other notions of optimization.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Natural language processing (NLP) allows programs to read, write and communicate in human languages.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specific problems include speech recognition, speech synthesis, machine translation, information extraction, information retrieval and question answering.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early work, based on Noam Chomsky's generative grammar and semantic networks, had difficulty with word-sense disambiguation unless restricted to small domains called "micro-worlds" (due to the common sense knowledge problem).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Margaret Masterman believed that it was meaning and not grammar that was the key to understanding languages, and that thesauri and not dictionaries should be the basis of computational language structure.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Modern deep learning techniques for NLP include word embedding (representing words, typically as vectors encoding their meaning), transformers (a deep learning architecture using an attention mechanism), and others.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, generative pre-trained transformer (or "GPT") language models began to generate coherent text, and by 2023, these models were able to get human-level scores on the bar exam, SAT test, GRE test, and many other real-world applications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine perception is the ability to use input from sensors (such as cameras, microphones, wireless signals, active lidar, sonar, radar, and tactile sensors) to deduce aspects of the world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computer vision is the ability to analyze visual input.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The field includes speech recognition, image classification, facial recognition, object recognition, object tracking, and robotic perception.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Affective computing is a field that comprises systems that recognize, interpret, process, or simulate human feeling, emotion, and mood.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, some virtual assistants are programmed to speak conversationally or even to banter humorously; it makes them appear more sensitive to the emotional dynamics of human interaction, or to otherwise facilitate human–computer interaction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, this tends to give naïve users an unrealistic conception of the intelligence of existing computer agents.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moderate successes related to affective computing include textual sentiment analysis and, more recently, multimodal sentiment analysis, wherein AI classifies the effects displayed by a videotaped subject.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A machine with artificial general intelligence would be able to solve a wide variety of problems with breadth and versatility similar to human intelligence.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI research uses a wide variety of techniques to accomplish the goals above.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] State space search searches through a tree of possible states to try to find a goal state.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, planning algorithms search through trees of goals and subgoals, attempting to find a path to a target goal, a process called means-ends analysis.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Simple exhaustive searches are rarely sufficient for most real-world problems: the search space (the number of places to search) quickly grows to astronomical numbers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The result is a search that is too slow or never completes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] "Heuristics" or "rules of thumb" can help prioritize choices that are more likely to reach a goal.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Adversarial search is used for game-playing programs, such as chess or Go.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It searches through a tree of possible moves and countermoves, looking for a winning position.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Local search uses mathematical optimization to find a solution to a problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It begins with some form of guess and refines it incrementally.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Gradient descent is a type of local search that optimizes a set of numerical parameters by incrementally adjusting them to minimize a loss function.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Variants of gradient descent are commonly used to train neural networks, through the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Another type of local search is evolutionary computation, which aims to iteratively improve a set of candidate solutions by "mutating" and "recombining" them, selecting only the fittest to survive each generation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Distributed search processes can coordinate via swarm intelligence algorithms.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Two popular swarm algorithms used in search are particle swarm optimization (inspired by bird flocking) and ant colony optimization (inspired by ant trails).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal logic is used for reasoning and knowledge representation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deductive reasoning in logic is the process of proving a new statement (conclusion) from other statements that are given and assumed to be true (the premises).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Proofs can be structured as proof trees, in which nodes are labelled by sentences, and children nodes are connected to parent nodes by inference rules.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Given a problem and a set of premises, problem-solving reduces to searching for a proof tree whose root node is labelled by a solution of the problem and whose leaf nodes are labelled by premises or axioms.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the case of Horn clauses, problem-solving search can be performed by reasoning forwards from the premises or backwards from the problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the more general case of the clausal form of first-order logic, resolution is a single, axiom-free rule of inference, in which a problem is solved by proving a contradiction from premises that include the negation of the problem to be solved.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Inference in both Horn clause logic and first-order logic is undecidable, and therefore intractable.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, backward reasoning with Horn clauses, which underpins computation in the logic programming language Prolog, is Turing complete.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moreover, its efficiency is competitive with computation in other symbolic programming languages.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Fuzzy logic assigns a "degree of truth" between 0 and 1.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can therefore handle propositions that are vague and partially true.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Non-monotonic logics, including logic programming with negation as failure, are designed to handle default reasoning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other specialized versions of logic have been developed to describe many complex domains.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many problems in AI (including reasoning, planning, learning, perception, and robotics) require the agent to operate with incomplete or uncertain information.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI researchers have devised a number of tools to solve these problems using methods from probability theory and economics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Precise mathematical tools have been developed that analyze how an agent can make choices and plan, using decision theory, decision analysis, and information value theory.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These tools include models such as Markov decision processes, dynamic decision networks, game theory and mechanism design.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Bayesian networks are a tool that can be used for reasoning (using the Bayesian inference algorithm), learning (using the expectation–maximization algorithm), planning (using decision networks) and perception (using dynamic Bayesian networks).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Probabilistic algorithms can also be used for filtering, prediction, smoothing, and finding explanations for streams of data, thus helping perception systems analyze processes that occur over time (e.g., hidden Markov models or Kalman filters).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The simplest AI applications can be divided into two types: classifiers (e.g., "if shiny then diamond"), on one hand, and controllers (e.g., "if diamond then pick up"), on the other hand.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Classifiers are functions that use pattern matching to determine the closest match.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] They can be fine-tuned based on chosen examples using supervised learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each pattern (also called an "observation") is labeled with a certain predefined class.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] All the observations combined with their class labels are known as a data set.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] When a new observation is received, that observation is classified based on previous experience.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are many kinds of classifiers in use.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision tree is the simplest and most widely used symbolic machine learning algorithm.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] K-nearest neighbor algorithm was the most widely used analogical AI until the mid-1990s, and Kernel methods such as the support vector machine (SVM) displaced k-nearest neighbor in the 1990s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The naive Bayes classifier is reportedly the "most widely used learner" at Google, due in part to its scalability.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks are also used as classifiers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] An artificial neural network is based on a collection of nodes also known as artificial neurons, which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] It is trained to recognise patterns; once trained, it can recognise those patterns in fresh data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is an input, at least one hidden layer of nodes and an output.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each node applies a function and once the weight crosses its specified threshold, the data is transmitted to the next layer.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least 2 hidden layers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Learning algorithms for neural networks use local search to choose the weights that will get the right output for each input during training.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The most common training technique is the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks learn to model complex relationships between inputs and outputs and find patterns in data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In theory, a neural network can learn any function.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In feedforward neural networks the signal passes in only one direction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The term perceptron typically refers to a single-layer neural network.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In contrast, deep learning uses many layers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNNs) feed the output signal back into the input, which allows short-term memories of previous input events.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Long short-term memory networks (LSTMs) are recurrent neural networks that better preserve longterm dependencies and are less sensitive to the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) use layers of kernels to more efficiently process local patterns.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] This local processing is especially important in image processing, where the early CNN layers typically identify simple local patterns such as edges and curves, with subsequent layers detecting more complex patterns like textures, and eventually whole objects.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning uses several layers of neurons between the network's inputs and outputs.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The multiple layers can progressively extract higher-level features from the raw input.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, in image processing, lower layers may identify edges, while higher layers may identify the concepts relevant to a human such as digits, letters, or faces.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning has profoundly improved the performance of programs in many important subfields of artificial intelligence, including computer vision, speech recognition, natural language processing, image classification, and others.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The reason that deep learning performs so well in so many applications is not known as of 2021.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPT) are large language models (LLMs) that generate text based on the semantic relationships between words in sentences.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Text-based GPT models are pre-trained on a large corpus of text that can be from the Internet.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The pretraining consists of predicting the next token (a token being usually a word, subword, or punctuation).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Throughout this pretraining, GPT models accumulate knowledge about the world and can then generate human-like text by repeatedly predicting the next token.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Typically, a subsequent training phase makes the model more truthful, useful, and harmless, usually with a technique called reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current GPT models are prone to generating falsehoods called "hallucinations".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These can be reduced with RLHF and quality data, but the problem has been getting worse for reasoning systems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Such systems are used in chatbots, which allow people to ask a question or request a task in simple text.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current models and services include ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Copilot, and Meta AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Multimodal GPT models can process different types of data (modalities) such as images, videos, sound, and text.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specialized programming languages such as Prolog were used in early AI research, but general-purpose programming languages like Python have become predominant.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The transistor density in integrated circuits has been observed to roughly double every 18 months—a trend known as Moore's law, named after the Intel co-founder Gordon Moore, who first identified it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Improvements in GPUs have been even faster, a trend sometimes called Huang's law, named after Nvidia co-founder and CEO Jensen Huang.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The deployment of AI may be overseen by a chief automation officer (CAO).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AlphaFold 2 (2021) demonstrated the ability to approximate, in hours rather than months, the 3D structure of a protein.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2023, it was reported that AI-guided drug discovery helped find a class of antibiotics capable of killing two different types of drug-resistant bacteria.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to accelerate the search for Parkinson's disease drug treatments.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Their aim was to identify compounds that block the clumping, or aggregation, of alpha-synuclein (the protein that characterises Parkinson's disease).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] They were able to speed up the initial screening process ten-fold and reduce the cost by a thousand-fold.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is increasingly being used in medical diagnostics, including the detection of diseases such as lung cancer from medical imaging like CT scans.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] A 2026 *Nature* article titled "Dozens of AI disease-prediction models were trained on dubious data" highlighted the use of unreliable data being used to train AI medical prediction models for stroke and diabetes in 125 research articles.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Evidence suggested some of the AI tools that were developed on unreliable data had been used on patients, although it was not clear if there were adverse outcomes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game playing programs have been used since the 1950s to demonstrate and test AI's most advanced techniques.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep Blue became the first computer chess-playing system to beat a reigning world chess champion, Garry Kasparov, on 11 May 1997.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2011, in a *Jeopardy!* quiz show exhibition match, IBM's question answering system, Watson, defeated the two greatest *Jeopardy!* champions, Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, by a significant margin.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In March 2016, AlphaGo won 4 out of 5 games of Go in a match with Go champion Lee Sedol, becoming the first computer Go-playing system to beat a professional Go player without handicaps.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Then, in 2017, it defeated Ke Jie, who was the best Go player in the world.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other programs handle imperfect-information games, such as the poker-playing program Pluribus.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] DeepMind developed increasingly generalistic reinforcement learning models, such as with MuZero, which could be trained to play chess, Go, or Atari games.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, DeepMind's AlphaStar achieved grandmaster level in StarCraft II, a particularly challenging real-time strategy game that involves incomplete knowledge of what happens on the map.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2021, an AI agent competed in a PlayStation Gran Turismo competition, winning against four of the world's best Gran Turismo drivers using deep reinforcement learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, Google DeepMind introduced SIMA, a type of AI capable of autonomously playing nine previously unseen open-world video games by observing screen output, as well as executing short, specific tasks in response to natural language instructions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In mathematics, probabilistic large language models are versatile, but can also produce wrong answers in the form of hallucinations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The Alibaba Group developed a version of its *Qwen* models called *Qwen2-Math*, that achieved state-of-the-art performance on several mathematical benchmarks, including 84% accuracy on the MATH dataset of competition mathematics problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In January 2025, Microsoft proposed the technique *rStar-Math* that leverages Monte Carlo tree search and step-by-step reasoning, enabling a relatively small language model like *Qwen-7B* to solve 53% of the AIME 2024 and 90% of the MATH benchmark problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] When natural language is used to describe mathematical problems, converters can transform such prompts into a formal language such as Lean to define mathematical tasks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The experimental model *Gemini Deep Think* accepts natural language prompts directly and achieved gold medal results in the International Math Olympiad of 2025.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Topological deep learning integrates various topological approaches.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] According to Nicolas Firzli, director of the World Pensions & Investments Forum, it may be too early to see the emergence of highly innovative AI-informed financial products and services.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Various countries are deploying AI military applications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The main applications enhance command and control, communications, sensors, integration and interoperability.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Research is targeting intelligence collection and analysis, logistics, cyber operations, information operations, and semiautonomous and autonomous vehicles.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies enable coordination of sensors and effectors, threat detection and identification, marking of enemy positions, target acquisition, coordination and deconfliction of distributed Joint Fires between networked combat vehicles, both human-operated and autonomous.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI has been used in military operations in Iraq, Syria, Israel and Ukraine.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) is a subfield of artificial intelligence (AI) that uses generative models to generate text, images, videos, audio, software code (vibe coding) or other forms of data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These models learn the underlying patterns and structures of their training data, and use them to generate new data in response to input, which often takes the form of natural language prompts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are software entities designed to perceive their environment, make decisions, and take actions autonomously to achieve specific goals.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] These agents can interact with users, their environment, or other agents.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are used in various applications, including virtual assistants, chatbots, autonomous vehicles, game-playing systems, and industrial robotics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents operate within the constraints of their programming, available computational resources, and hardware limitations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] This means they are restricted to performing tasks within their defined scope and have finite memory and processing capabilities.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In real-world applications, AI agents often face time constraints for decision-making and action execution.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many AI agents incorporate learning algorithms, enabling them to improve their performance over time through experience or training.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Using machine learning, AI agents can adapt to new situations and optimise their behaviour for their designated tasks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Microsoft introduced Copilot Search in February 2023 under the name Bing Chat.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Copilot Search provides AI-generated summaries.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Google introduced an AI Mode at its Google I/O event on 20 May 2025.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] Applications of AI in this domain include AI-enabled menstruation and fertility trackers that analyze user data to offer predictions, AI-integrated sex toys (e.g., teledildonics), AI-generated sexual education content, and AI agents that simulate sexual and romantic partners (e.g., Replika).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is also used for the production of non-consensual deepfake pornography, raising significant ethical and legal concerns.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies have also been used to attempt to identify online gender-based violence and online sexual grooming of minors.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In a 2017 survey, one in five companies reported having incorporated "AI" in some offerings or processes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the field of evacuation and disaster management, AI has been used to investigate patterns in large-scale and small-scale evacuations using historical data from GPS, videos or social media.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] During the 2024 Indian elections, US$50 million was spent on authorized AI-generated content, notably by creating deepfakes of allied (including sometimes deceased) politicians to better engage with voters, and by translating speeches to various local languages.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] The use of generative AI by law firms for legal research resulted in the creation of the global "AI Hallucination Cases" database, in April 2025, established by HEC Paris and Sciences Po legal data analysis lecturer Damien Charlotin.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p01] By 2026, judges had issued sanctions and bar associations had issued warnings due to attorney submissions to the courts containing fabricated case law citations hallucinated by AI tools.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI has potential benefits and potential risks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI may be able to advance science and find solutions for serious problems: Demis Hassabis of DeepMind hopes to "solve intelligence, and then use that to solve everything else".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, as the use of AI has become widespread, several unintended consequences and risks have been identified.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In-production systems can sometimes not factor ethics and bias into their AI training processes, especially when the AI algorithms are inherently unexplainable in deep learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning algorithms require large amounts of data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The techniques used to acquire this data have raised concerns about privacy, surveillance and copyright.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI-powered devices and services, such as virtual assistants and IoT products, continuously collect personal information, raising concerns about intrusive data gathering and unauthorized access by third parties.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The loss of privacy is further exacerbated by AI's ability to process and combine vast amounts of data, potentially leading to a surveillance society where individual activities are constantly monitored and analyzed without adequate safeguards or transparency.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Sensitive user data collected may include online activity records, geolocation data, video, or audio.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, in order to build speech recognition algorithms, Amazon has recorded millions of private conversations and allowed temporary workers to listen to and transcribe some of them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Opinions about this widespread surveillance range from those who see it as a necessary evil to those for whom it is clearly unethical and a violation of the right to privacy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI developers argue that this is the only way to deliver valuable applications and have developed several techniques that attempt to preserve privacy while still obtaining the data, such as data aggregation, de-identification and differential privacy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since 2016, some privacy experts, such as Cynthia Dwork, have begun to view privacy in terms of fairness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Generative AI is often trained on unlicensed copyrighted works, including in domains such as images or computer code; the output is then used under the rationale of "fair use".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Experts disagree about how well and under what circumstances this rationale will hold up in courts of law; relevant factors may include "the purpose and character of the use of the copyrighted work" and "the effect upon the potential market for the copyrighted work".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Website owners can indicate that they do not want their content scraped via a "robots.txt" file.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, some companies will scrape content regardless because the robots.txt file has no real authority.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, leading authors (including John Grisham and Jonathan Franzen) sued AI companies for using their work to train generative AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another discussed approach is to envision a separate *sui generis* system of protection for creations generated by AI to ensure fair attribution and compensation for human authors.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The commercial AI scene is dominated by Big Tech companies such as Alphabet Inc., Amazon, Apple Inc., Meta Platforms, and Microsoft.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some of these players already own the vast majority of existing cloud infrastructure and computing power from data centers, allowing them to entrench further in the marketplace.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Technology companies have built electricity and artificial intelligence infrastructure to facilitate the AI boom of the 2020s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2025 report from the consulting firm McKinsey & Company estimated that by 2030, $2.7 trillion would be invested into AI infrastructure and data centers in the US, surpassing World War II's Manhattan Project every month.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In January 2024, the International Energy Agency (IEA) released *Electricity 2024, Analysis and Forecast to 2026*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is the first IEA report to make projections for data centers and power consumption by AI and cryptocurrency.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The report states that power demand for these uses might double by 2026, with the additional power consumption equaling that of Japan.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Power consumption by AI is responsible for an increase in fossil fuel use, and has delayed closings of obsolete, carbon-emitting coal energy facilities.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A ChatGPT search involves the use of 10 times the electrical energy as a Google search.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Data centers' need for more and more electrical power is such that they might max out the electrical grid.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Big Tech companies counter that AI can be used to maximize the utilization of the grid by all.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that big AI companies have begun negotiations with the US nuclear power providers to provide electricity to the data centers.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2024 Amazon purchased a Pennsylvania nuclear-powered data center for US$650 million.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In September 2024, Microsoft announced an agreement with Constellation Energy to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide Microsoft with 100% of all electric power produced by the plant for 20 years.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Reopening the plant, which suffered a partial nuclear meltdown of its Unit 2 reactor in 1979, will require Constellation to get through strict regulatory processes which will include extensive safety scrutiny from the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] If approved (this will be the first ever US re-commissioning of a nuclear plant), over 835 megawatts of power – enough for 800,000 homes – of energy will be produced.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The cost for re-opening and upgrading is estimated at US$1.6 billion and is dependent on tax breaks for nuclear power contained in the 2022 US Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] As of 2024, the US government and the state of Michigan have been investing almost US$2 billion to reopen the Palisades Nuclear reactor on Lake Michigan.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Closed since 2022, the plant was planned to be reopened in October 2025.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the last approval in September 2023, Taiwan suspended the approval of data centers north of Taoyuan with a capacity of more than 5 MW in 2024, due to power supply shortages.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Taiwan aims to phase out nuclear power by 2025.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Singapore imposed a ban on the opening of data centers in 2019 due to electric power, but in 2022, lifted this ban.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 November 2024, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) rejected an application submitted by Talen Energy for approval to supply some electricity from the nuclear power station Susquehanna to Amazon's data center.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to the Commission Chairman Willie L.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Phillips, it is a burden on the electricity grid as well as a significant cost shifting concern to households and other business sectors.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2025, a report prepared by the IEA estimated the greenhouse gas emissions from the energy consumption of AI at 180 million tons.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2035, these emissions could rise to 300–500 million tonnes depending on what measures will be taken.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is below 1.5% of the energy sector emissions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The emissions reduction potential of AI was estimated at 5% of the energy sector emissions, but rebound effects (for example if people switch from public transport to autonomous cars) can reduce it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] YouTube, Facebook and others use recommender systems to guide users to more content.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] These AI programs were given the goal of maximizing user engagement (that is, the only goal was to keep people watching).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI learned that users tended to choose misinformation, conspiracy theories, and extreme partisan content, and, to keep them watching, the AI recommended more of it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Users also tended to watch more content on the same subject, so the AI led people into filter bubbles where they received multiple versions of the same misinformation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This convinced many users that the misinformation was true, and ultimately undermined trust in institutions, the media and the government.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI program had correctly learned to maximize its goal, but the result was harmful to society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the U.S. election in 2016, major technology companies took some steps to mitigate the problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 2020s, generative AI began to create images, audio, and texts that are virtually indistinguishable from real photographs, recordings, or human writing, while realistic AI-generated videos became feasible in the mid-2020s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is possible for bad actors to use this technology to create massive amounts of misinformation and computational propaganda through techniques such as deepfakes.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI pioneer and Nobel Prize-winning computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton expressed concern about AI enabling "authoritarian leaders to manipulate their electorates" on a large scale, among other risks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The ability to influence electorates has been proved in at least one study.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This same study shows more inaccurate statements from the models when they advocate for candidates of the political right.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI researchers at Microsoft, OpenAI, universities and other organisations have suggested using "personhood credentials" as a way to overcome online deception enabled by AI models.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning applications can be biased if they learn from biased data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The developers may not be aware that the bias exists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Discriminatory behavior by some LLMs can be observed in their output.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias can be introduced by the way training data is selected and by the way a model is deployed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] If a biased algorithm is used to make decisions that can seriously harm people (as it can in medicine, finance, recruitment, housing or policing) then the algorithm may cause discrimination.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of fairness studies how to prevent harms from algorithmic biases.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 28 June 2015, Google Photos's new image labeling feature mistakenly identified Jacky Alcine and a friend as "gorillas" because they were black.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The system was trained on a dataset that contained very few images of black people, a problem called "sample size disparity".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Google "fixed" this problem by preventing the system from labelling *anything* as a "gorilla".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eight years later, in 2023, Google Photos still could not identify a gorilla, and neither could similar products from Apple, Facebook, Microsoft and Amazon.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] COMPAS is a commercial program widely used by U.S. courts to assess the likelihood of a defendant becoming a recidivist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, Julia Angwin at ProPublica discovered that COMPAS exhibited racial bias, despite the fact that the program was not told the races of the defendants.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Although the error rate for both whites and blacks was calibrated equal at exactly 61%, the errors for each race were different—the system consistently overestimated the chance that a black person would re-offend and would underestimate the chance that a white person would not re-offend.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2017, several researchers showed that it was mathematically impossible for COMPAS to accommodate all possible measures of fairness when the base rates of re-offense were different for whites and blacks in the data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A program can make biased decisions even if the data does not explicitly mention a problematic feature (such as "race" or "gender").
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The feature will correlate with other features (like "address", "shopping history" or "first name"), and the program will make the same decisions based on these features as it would on "race" or "gender".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Criticism of COMPAS highlighted that machine learning models are designed to make "predictions" that are only valid if we assume that the future will resemble the past.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] If they are trained on data that includes the results of racist decisions in the past, machine learning models must predict that racist decisions will be made in the future.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] If an application then uses these predictions as *recommendations*, some of these "recommendations" will likely be racist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Thus, machine learning is not well suited to help make decisions in areas where there is hope that the future will be *better* than the past.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is descriptive rather than prescriptive.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias and unfairness may go undetected because the developers are overwhelmingly white and male: among AI engineers, about 4% are black and 20% are women.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are various conflicting definitions and mathematical models of fairness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] These notions depend on ethical assumptions, and are influenced by beliefs about society.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] One broad category is distributive fairness, which focuses on the outcomes, often identifying groups and seeking to compensate for statistical disparities.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Representational fairness tries to ensure that AI systems do not reinforce negative stereotypes or render certain groups invisible.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Procedural fairness focuses on the decision process rather than the outcome.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The most relevant notions of fairness may depend on the context, notably the type of AI application and the stakeholders.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The subjectivity in the notions of bias and fairness makes it difficult for companies to operationalize them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having access to sensitive attributes such as race or gender is also considered by many AI ethicists to be necessary in order to compensate for biases, but it may conflict with anti-discrimination laws.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the 2022 ACM Conference on Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency a paper reported that a CLIP‑based (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training) robotic system reproduced harmful gender‑ and race‑linked stereotypes in a simulated manipulation task.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many AI systems are so complex that their designers cannot explain how they reach their decisions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Particularly with deep neural networks, in which there are many non-linear relationships between inputs and outputs.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] But some popular explainability techniques exist.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is impossible to be certain that a program is operating correctly if no one knows how exactly it works.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] There have been many cases where a machine learning program passed rigorous tests, but nevertheless learned something different than what the programmers intended.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, a system that could identify skin diseases better than medical professionals was found to actually have a strong tendency to classify images with a ruler as "cancerous", because pictures of malignancies typically include a ruler to show the scale.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another machine learning system designed to help effectively allocate medical resources was found to classify patients with asthma as being at "low risk" of dying from pneumonia.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having asthma is actually a severe risk factor, but since the patients having asthma would usually get much more medical care, they were relatively unlikely to die according to the training data.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The correlation between asthma and low risk of dying from pneumonia was real, but misleading.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] People who have been harmed by an algorithm's decision have a right to an explanation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Doctors, for example, are expected to clearly and completely explain to their colleagues the reasoning behind any decision they make.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early drafts of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation in 2016 included an explicit statement that this right exists.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Industry experts noted that this is an unsolved problem with no solution in sight.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Regulators argued that nevertheless the harm is real: if the problem has no solution, the tools should not be used.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] DARPA established the XAI ("Explainable Artificial Intelligence") program in 2014 to try to solve these problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Several approaches aim to address the transparency problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] SHAP enables to visualise the contribution of each feature to the output.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] LIME can locally approximate a model's outputs with a simpler, interpretable model.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Multitask learning provides a large number of outputs in addition to the target classification.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] These other outputs can help developers deduce what the network has learned.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deconvolution, DeepDream and other generative methods can allow developers to see what different layers of a deep network for computer vision have learned, and produce output that can suggest what the network is learning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] For generative pre-trained transformers, Anthropic developed a technique based on dictionary learning that associates patterns of neuron activations with human-understandable concepts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence provides a number of tools that are useful to bad actors, such as authoritarian governments, terrorists, criminals or rogue states.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A lethal autonomous weapon is a machine that locates, selects and engages human targets without human supervision.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Widely available AI tools can be used by bad actors to develop inexpensive autonomous weapons and, if produced at scale, they are potentially weapons of mass destruction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Even when used in conventional warfare, they currently cannot reliably choose targets and could potentially kill an innocent person.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2014, 30 nations (including China) supported a ban on autonomous weapons under the United Nations' Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons, however the United States and others disagreed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2015, over fifty countries were reported to be researching battlefield robots.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI tools make it easier for authoritarian governments to efficiently control their citizens in several ways.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Face and voice recognition allow widespread surveillance.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning, operating this data, can classify potential enemies of the state and prevent them from hiding.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recommendation systems can precisely target propaganda and misinformation for maximum effect.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deepfakes and generative AI aid in producing misinformation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Advanced AI can make authoritarian centralized decision-making more competitive than liberal and decentralized systems such as markets.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It lowers the cost and difficulty of digital warfare and advanced spyware.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] All these technologies have been available since 2020 or earlier—AI facial recognition systems are already being used for mass surveillance in China.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are many other ways in which AI is expected to help bad actors, some of which can not be foreseen.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, machine-learning AI is able to design tens of thousands of toxic molecules in a matter of hours.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Economists have frequently highlighted the risks of redundancies from AI, and speculated about unemployment if there is no adequate social policy for full employment.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the past, technology has tended to increase rather than reduce total employment, but economists acknowledge that "we're in uncharted territory" with AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A survey of economists showed disagreement about whether the increasing use of robots and AI will cause a substantial increase in long-term unemployment, but they generally agree that it could be a net benefit if productivity gains are redistributed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Risk estimates vary; for example, in the 2010s, Michael Osborne and Carl Benedikt Frey estimated 47% of U.S. jobs are at "high risk" of potential automation, while an OECD report classified only 9% of U.S. jobs as "high risk".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The methodology of speculating about future employment levels has been criticised as lacking evidential foundation, and for implying that technology, rather than social policy, creates unemployment, as opposed to redundancies.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In April 2023, it was reported that 70% of the jobs for Chinese video game illustrators had been eliminated by generative artificial intelligence.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early-career workers showed decreasing employment rates in some AI-exposed occupations.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Unlike previous waves of automation, many middle-class jobs may be eliminated by artificial intelligence; *The Economist* stated in 2015 that "the worry that AI could do to white-collar jobs what steam power did to blue-collar ones during the Industrial Revolution" is "worth taking seriously".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Jobs at extreme risk range from paralegals to fast food cooks, while job demand is likely to increase for care-related professions ranging from personal healthcare to the clergy.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] With the increase of loneliness in the early 21st century, AI is sometimes identified as a potential source of relief to this problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It would be possible, via human-like qualities built into AI products, for individuals to assume that this need can be met by artificial means.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In some cases, people approach artificial intelligence for companionship when they believe that they would not find acceptance due to feeling outcast.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Examples of harm coming to humans from advanced chatbots have been reported in courts in the United States, with AI companies accused of creating products that endanger humans through emotional confusion or deception.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recent public debates in artificial intelligence have increasingly focused on its broader societal and ethical implications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It has been argued AI will become so powerful that humanity may irreversibly lose control of it.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This could, as physicist Stephen Hawking stated, "spell the end of the human race".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This scenario has been common in science fiction, when a computer or robot suddenly develops a human-like "self-awareness" (or "sentience" or "consciousness") and becomes a malevolent character.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] These sci-fi scenarios are misleading in several ways.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] First, AI does not require human-like sentience to be an existential risk.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Modern AI programs are given specific goals and use learning and intelligence to achieve them.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Philosopher Nick Bostrom argued that if one gives *almost any* goal to a sufficiently powerful AI, it may choose to destroy humanity to achieve it (he used the example of an automated paperclip factory that destroys the world to get more iron for paperclips).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Second, Yuval Noah Harari argues that AI does not require a robot body or physical control to pose an existential risk.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The essential parts of civilization are not physical.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Things like ideologies, law, government, money and the economy are built on language; they exist because there are stories that billions of people believe.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The current prevalence of misinformation suggests that an AI could use language to convince people to believe anything, even to take actions that are destructive.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Geoffrey Hinton said in 2025 that modern AI is particularly "good at persuasion" and getting better all the time.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] He asks, "Suppose you wanted to invade the capital of the US.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Do you have to go there and do it yourself?
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The opinions amongst experts and industry insiders are mixed, with sizable fractions both concerned and unconcerned by risk from eventual superintelligent AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Personalities such as Stephen Hawking, Bill Gates, and Elon Musk, as well as AI pioneers such as Geoffrey Hinton, Yoshua Bengio, Stuart Russell, Demis Hassabis, and Sam Altman, have expressed concerns about existential risk from AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2023, Geoffrey Hinton announced his resignation from Google in order to be able to "freely speak out about the risks of AI" without "considering how this impacts Google".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] He notably mentioned risks of an AI takeover, and stressed that in order to avoid the worst outcomes, establishing safety guidelines will require cooperation among those competing in use of AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, many leading AI experts endorsed the joint statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some other researchers were more optimistic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, after 2016, the study of current and future risks and possible solutions became a serious area of research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Friendly AI are machines that have been designed from the beginning to minimize risks and to make choices that benefit humans.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eliezer Yudkowsky, who coined the term, argues that developing friendly AI should be a higher research priority: it may require a large investment and it must be completed before AI becomes an existential risk.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machines with intelligence have the potential to use their intelligence to make ethical decisions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics provides machines with ethical principles and procedures for resolving ethical dilemmas.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics is also called computational morality, and was founded at an AAAI symposium in 2005.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Other approaches include Wendell Wallach's "artificial moral agents" and Stuart J.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Russell's three principles for developing provably beneficial machines.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Active organizations in the AI open-source community include Hugging Face, Google, EleutherAI and Meta.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Various AI models, such as Llama 2, Mistral or Stable Diffusion, have been made open-weight, meaning that their architecture and trained parameters (the "weights") are publicly available.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models can be freely fine-tuned, which allows companies to specialize them with their own data and for their own use-case.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models are useful for research and innovation but can also be misused.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since they can be fine-tuned, any built-in security measure, such as objecting to harmful requests, can be trained away until it becomes ineffective.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some researchers warn that future AI models may develop dangerous capabilities (such as the potential to drastically facilitate bioterrorism) and that once released on the Internet, they cannot be deleted everywhere if needed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] They recommend pre-release audits and cost-benefit analyses.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence projects can be guided by ethical considerations during the design, development, and implementation of an AI system.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The UK AI Safety Institute released in 2024 a testing toolset called 'Inspect' for AI safety evaluations available under an MIT open-source licence which is freely available on GitHub and can be improved with third-party packages.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It can be used to evaluate AI models in a range of areas including core knowledge, ability to reason, and autonomous capabilities.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulation of artificial intelligence is the development of public sector policies and laws for promoting and regulating AI; it is therefore related to the broader regulation of algorithms.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulatory and policy landscape for AI is an emerging issue in jurisdictions globally.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Index at Stanford, the annual number of AI-related laws passed in the 127 survey countries jumped from one passed in 2016 to 37 passed in 2022 alone.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Between 2016 and 2020, more than 30 countries adopted dedicated strategies for AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Most EU member states had released national AI strategies, as had Canada, China, India, Japan, Mauritius, the Russian Federation, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, U.S., and Vietnam.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Others were in the process of elaborating their own AI strategy, including Bangladesh, Malaysia and Tunisia.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Global Partnership on Artificial Intelligence was launched in June 2020, stating a need for AI to be developed in accordance with human rights and democratic values, to ensure public confidence and trust in the technology.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Henry Kissinger, Eric Schmidt, and Daniel Huttenlocher published a joint statement in November 2021 calling for a government commission to regulate AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, OpenAI leaders published recommendations for the governance of superintelligence, which they believe may happen in less than 10 years.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, the United Nations also launched an advisory body to provide recommendations on AI governance; the body comprises technology company executives, government officials and academics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 August 2024, the EU Artificial Intelligence Act entered into force, establishing the first comprehensive EU-wide AI regulation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe created the first international legally binding treaty on AI, called the "Framework Convention on Artificial Intelligence and Human Rights, Democracy and the Rule of Law".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It was adopted by the European Union, the United States, the United Kingdom, and other signatories.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2022 Ipsos survey, attitudes towards AI varied greatly by country; 78% of Chinese citizens, but only 35% of Americans, agreed that "products and services using AI have more benefits than drawbacks".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2023 Reuters/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans agree, and 22% disagree, that AI poses risks to humanity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2023 Fox News poll, 35% of Americans thought it "very important", and an additional 41% thought it "somewhat important", for the federal government to regulate AI, versus 13% responding "not very important" and 8% responding "not at all important".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In November 2023, the first global AI Safety Summit was held in Bletchley Park in the UK to discuss the near and far term risks of AI and the possibility of mandatory and voluntary regulatory frameworks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] 28 countries including the United States, China, and the European Union issued a declaration at the start of the summit, calling for international co-operation to manage the challenges and risks of artificial intelligence.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2024 at the AI Seoul Summit, 16 global AI tech companies agreed to safety commitments on the development of AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2026, the United Nations convened the inaugural meeting of the Independent International Scientific Panel on AI, a 40-member expert body established under the Global Digital Compact to produce annual evidence-based reports on AI's societal impacts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of mechanical or "formal" reasoning began with philosophers and mathematicians in antiquity.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of logic led directly to Alan Turing's theory of computation, which suggested that a machine, by shuffling symbols as simple as "0" and "1", could simulate any conceivable form of mathematical reasoning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This, along with concurrent discoveries in cybernetics, information theory and neurobiology, led researchers to consider the possibility of building an "electronic brain".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of AI research was founded at a workshop at Dartmouth College in 1956.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The first AI program, Logic Theorist, was presented at the workshop, created by future Turing Award winner Allen Newell and future Nobel Laureate Herbert A.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many of the workshop attendees became the leaders of AI research in the 1960s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] They and their students produced programs that the press described as "astonishing": computers were learning checkers strategies, solving word problems in algebra, proving logical theorems and speaking English.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence laboratories were set up at a number of British and U.S. universities in the latter 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Researchers in the 1960s and the 1970s were convinced that their methods would eventually succeed in creating a machine with general intelligence and considered this the goal of their field.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1965 Herbert Simon predicted, "machines will be capable, within twenty years, of doing any work a man can do".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1967 Marvin Minsky agreed, writing that "within a generation ... the problem of creating 'artificial intelligence' will substantially be solved".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] They had, however, underestimated the difficulty of the problem.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1974, both the U.S. and British governments cut off exploratory research in response to the criticism of Sir James Lighthill and ongoing pressure from the U.S.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Congress to fund more productive projects.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Minsky and Papert's book *Perceptrons* was understood as proving that artificial neural networks would never be useful for solving real-world tasks, thus discrediting the approach altogether.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The "AI winter", a period when obtaining funding for AI projects was difficult, followed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 1980s, AI research was revived by the commercial success of expert systems, a form of AI program that simulated the knowledge and analytical skills of human experts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 1985, the market for AI had reached over a billion dollars.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the same time, Japan's fifth generation computer project inspired the U.S. and British governments to restore funding for academic research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, beginning with the collapse of the Lisp Machine market in 1987, AI once again fell into disrepute, and a second, longer-lasting winter began.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Up to this point, most of AI's funding had gone to projects that used high-level symbols to represent mental objects like plans, goals, beliefs, and known facts.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the 1980s, some researchers began to doubt that this approach would be able to imitate all the processes of human cognition, especially perception, robotics, learning and pattern recognition, and began to look into "sub-symbolic" approaches.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Rodney Brooks rejected "representation" in general and focussed directly on engineering machines that move and survive.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Judea Pearl, Lotfi Zadeh, and others developed methods that handled incomplete and uncertain information by making reasonable guesses rather than precise logic.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] But the most important development was the revival of "connectionism", including neural network research, by Geoffrey Hinton and others.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1990, Yann LeCun successfully showed that convolutional neural networks can recognize handwritten digits, the first of many successful applications of neural networks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI gradually restored its reputation in the late 1990s and early 21st century by exploiting formal mathematical methods and by finding specific solutions to specific problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] This "narrow" and "formal" focus allowed researchers to produce verifiable results and collaborate with other fields (such as statistics, economics and mathematics).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2000, solutions developed by AI researchers were being widely used, although in the 1990s they were rarely described as "artificial intelligence" (a tendency known as the AI effect).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, several academic researchers became concerned that AI was no longer pursuing its original goal of creating versatile, fully intelligent machines.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Beginning around 2002, they founded the subfield of artificial general intelligence (or "AGI"), which had several well-funded institutions by the 2010s.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning began to dominate industry benchmarks in 2012 and was adopted throughout the field.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] For many specific tasks, other methods were abandoned.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success was based on both hardware improvements (faster computers, graphics processing units, cloud computing) and access to large amounts of data (including curated datasets, such as ImageNet).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success led to an enormous increase in interest and funding in AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The amount of machine learning research (measured by total publications) increased by 50% in the years 2015–2019.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, issues of fairness and the misuse of technology were catapulted into center stage at machine learning conferences, publications vastly increased, funding became available, and many researchers re-focussed their careers on these issues.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The alignment problem became a serious field of academic study.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the late 2010s and early 2020s, AGI companies began to deliver programs that created enormous interest.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2015, AlphaGo, developed by DeepMind, beat the world champion Go player.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] The program taught only the game's rules and developed a strategy by itself.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] GPT-3 is a large language model that was released in 2020 by OpenAI and is capable of generating high-quality human-like text.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] ChatGPT, launched on 30 November 2022, became the fastest-growing consumer software application in history, gaining over 100 million users in two months.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] It marked what is widely regarded as AI's breakout year, bringing it into the public consciousness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] These programs, and others, inspired an aggressive AI boom, where large companies began investing billions of dollars in AI research.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Impacts, about US$50 billion annually was invested in "AI" around 2022 in the U.S. alone and about 20% of the new U.S. computer science PhD graduates have specialized in "AI".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] About 800,000 "AI"-related U.S. job openings existed in 2022.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to PitchBook research, 22% of newly funded startups in 2024 claimed to be AI companies.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosophical debates have historically sought to determine the nature of intelligence and how to make intelligent machines.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another major focus has been whether machines can be conscious, and the associated ethical implications.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Many other topics in philosophy are relevant to AI, such as epistemology and free will.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Rapid advancements have intensified public discussions on the philosophy and ethics of AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Alan Turing investigated whether machines can show intelligent behaviour and think.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] In 1950, he proposed the Turing test, which measures the ability of a machine to simulate human conversation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Since we can only observe the behavior of the machine, it does not matter if it is "actually" thinking or literally has a "mind".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig agree with Turing that intelligence must be defined in terms of external behavior, not internal structure.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, they are critical that the test requires the machine to imitate humans.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] McCarthy defines intelligence as "the computational part of the ability to achieve goals in the world".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another AI founder, Marvin Minsky, similarly describes it as "the ability to solve hard problems".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* defines it as the study of agents that perceive their environment and take actions that maximize their chances of achieving defined goals.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The many differing definitions of AI have been critically analyzed.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] During the 2020s AI boom, the term has been used as a marketing buzzword to promote products and services which do not use AI.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The International Organization for Standardization describes an AI system as a "an engineered system that generates outputs such as content, forecasts, recommendations, or decisions for a given set of human‑defined objectives, and can operate with varying levels of automation".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI systems are designed to operate with varying levels of autonomy".
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] No established unifying theory or paradigm has guided AI research for most of its history.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The unprecedented success of statistical machine learning in the 2010s eclipsed all other approaches (so much so that some sources, especially in the business world, use the term "artificial intelligence" to mean "machine learning with neural networks").
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] This approach is mostly sub-symbolic, soft and narrow.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Symbolic AI (or "GOFAI") simulated the high-level conscious reasoning that people use when they solve puzzles, express legal reasoning and do mathematics.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] It was highly successful at some "intelligent" tasks such as algebra or IQ tests.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, the symbolic approach failed on many tasks that humans solve easily, such as learning, recognizing an object or commonsense reasoning.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Moravec's paradox is the discovery that high-level "intelligent" tasks were easy for AI, but low level "instinctive" tasks were extremely difficult.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosopher Hubert Dreyfus had argued since the 1960s that human expertise depends on unconscious instinct rather than conscious symbol manipulation, and on having a "feel" for the situation, rather than explicit symbolic knowledge.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Although his arguments had been ridiculed and ignored when they were first presented, eventually, AI research came to agree with him.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The issue is not resolved: sub-symbolic reasoning can make many of the same inscrutable mistakes that human intuition does, such as algorithmic bias.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The emerging field of neuro-symbolic artificial intelligence attempts to bridge the two approaches.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Neats" hope that intelligent behavior is described using simple, elegant principles (such as logic, optimization, or neural networks).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Scruffies" expect that it necessarily requires solving a large number of unrelated problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Neats defend their programs with theoretical rigor, scruffies rely mainly on incremental testing to see if they work.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue was actively discussed in the 1970s and 1980s, but eventually was seen as irrelevant.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Finding a provably correct or optimal solution is intractable for many important problems.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing is a set of techniques, including genetic algorithms, fuzzy logic and neural networks, that are tolerant of imprecision, uncertainty, partial truth and approximation.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing was introduced in the late 1980s and most successful AI programs in the 21st century are examples of soft computing with neural networks.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI researchers are divided as to whether to pursue the goals of artificial general intelligence and superintelligence directly or to solve as many specific problems as possible (narrow AI) in hopes these solutions will lead indirectly to the field's long-term goals.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] General intelligence is difficult to define and difficult to measure, and modern AI has had more verifiable successes by focusing on specific problems with specific solutions.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The sub-field of artificial general intelligence studies this area exclusively.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] There is no settled consensus in philosophy of mind on whether a machine can have a mind, consciousness and mental states in the same sense that human beings do.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue considers the internal experiences of the machine, rather than its external behavior.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Mainstream AI research considers this issue irrelevant because it does not affect the goals of the field: to build machines that can solve problems using intelligence.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig add that "[t]he additional project of making a machine conscious in exactly the way humans are is not one that we are equipped to take on." However, the question has become central to the philosophy of mind.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] It is also typically the central question at issue in artificial intelligence in fiction.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] David Chalmers identified two problems in understanding the mind, which he named the "hard" and "easy" problems of consciousness.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The easy problem is understanding how the brain processes signals, makes plans and controls behavior.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] The hard problem is explaining how this *feels* or why it should feel like anything at all, assuming we are right in thinking that it truly does feel like something (Dennett's consciousness illusionism says this is an illusion).
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] While human information processing is easy to explain, human subjective experience is difficult to explain.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] For example, it is easy to imagine a color-blind person who has learned to identify which objects in their field of view are red, but it is not clear what would be required for the person to *know what red looks like*.
[src:harold-garfinkel/artificial-intelligence-p03] Computationalism is the position in the philosophy of mind that the human mind is an information processing system and that thinking is a form of computing.
